# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: abstract-expressionism
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:abstract-expressionism/9th-street-art-exhibition] The **9th Street Art Exhibition of Paintings and Sculpture** is the official title artist Franz Kline hand-lettered onto the poster he designed for the **Ninth Street Show** (May 21-June 10, 1951).
[src:abstract-expressionism/9th-street-art-exhibition] Now considered historic, the artist-led exhibition marked the formal debut of Abstract Expressionism, and the first American art movement with international influence.
[src:abstract-expressionism/9th-street-art-exhibition] The School of Paris, long the headquarters of the global art market, typically launched new movements, so there was both financial and cultural fall-out when all the excitement was suddenly emanating from New York.
[src:abstract-expressionism/9th-street-art-exhibition] The postwar New York avant-garde, artists like Willem de Kooning and Jackson Pollock, would soon become "art stars," commanding large sums and international attention.
[src:abstract-expressionism/9th-street-art-exhibition] The artist-led show was intended to make names — and it did.
[src:abstract-expressionism/9th-street-art-exhibition] Word of the exhibition slipped out prior to the Monday night preview, but that only added to the interest.
[src:abstract-expressionism/9th-street-art-exhibition] Author Mary Gabriel writes, "Nothing sold, but no one cared.
[src:abstract-expressionism/9th-street-art-exhibition] During the late 1940s and early 1950s, dozens of painters and sculptors all had art studios in lower Manhattan between 8th and 12th streets and First and Sixth Avenues.
[src:abstract-expressionism/9th-street-art-exhibition] Collectively known as the Downtown Group, many of them were former Federal Art Project artists, including Philip Pavia, Willem de Kooning, Landes Lewitin, Franz Kline and Jack Tworkov.
[src:abstract-expressionism/9th-street-art-exhibition] Several had also served in the military during World War II.
[src:abstract-expressionism/9th-street-art-exhibition] In 1949, members of the Downtown Group, helmed by Philip Pavia, created a more structured group that met regularly on 39 East 8th Street, and came to be known as "The Club." Weekly discussions at the Club led to the idea of organizing the 9th Street Art Exhibition as a launching pad.
[src:abstract-expressionism/9th-street-art-exhibition] "Since few of them had ever received any significant notice," the *New Yorker*'s Claudia Roth Pierpont writes*,* describing both the artists and the exhibition's selection process, "the rush to participate was so intense that everyone was limited to a single piece.
[src:abstract-expressionism/9th-street-art-exhibition] Even in this renegade atmosphere," she continues, "there was some initial discussion of whether including women in the exhibition would diminish its chance of being taken seriously.
[src:abstract-expressionism/9th-street-art-exhibition] Prior to the show, artist Franz Kline designed and created of all of the promotional materials, including the poster that gave the show its official name.
[src:abstract-expressionism/9th-street-art-exhibition] During the event, Aaron Siskind, also a New York School "member," documented the exhibit with a series of photographs.
[src:abstract-expressionism/9th-street-art-exhibition] Critical response after the Ninth Street Show encouraged and helped define early abstract expressionism, while also promoting it.
[src:abstract-expressionism/9th-street-art-exhibition] Critic Harold Rosenberg's "famous 1952 essay, 'The American Action Painters,' [which] effectively likened artists such as Willem de Kooning and Franz Kline to heroic existentialists wrestling with self-expression" is one good example.
[src:abstract-expressionism/9th-street-art-exhibition] A less enthusiastic public, however, meant that few local galleries mounted shows featuring members of the group.
[src:abstract-expressionism/9th-street-art-exhibition] The Stable Gallery, a converted horse stable, located at 924 7th Avenue and 58th Street in Manhattan, was an exception, and as host of the New York Painting and Sculpture Annuals from 1953–57, it exhibited some of the "Ninth Street Show" artists.
[src:abstract-expressionism/9th-street-art-exhibition] Sixty-one men and eleven women participated in the Ninth Street Art Exhibition.
[src:abstract-expressionism/9th-street-art-exhibition] The best-selling book ignited interest in the underappreciated women of abstract expressionism and in women artists, generally.
[src:abstract-expressionism/9th-street-art-exhibition] On April 24, 2019, *The Hollywood Reporter* published an exclusive, reporting that Amazon Studios had optioned Gabriel's book for Amy Sherman-Palladino and Daniel Palladino to develop into a series.
[src:abstract-expressionism/9th-street-art-exhibition] The University of California, Los Angeles (UCLA) also developed an art history class called "Ninth Street Women: The Women of Abstract Expressionism," which assigned Gabriel's book as a text to the influential women artists in the 9th Street Show.
[src:abstract-expressionism/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] Seurat's composition, painted on a large canvas, includes a number of Parisians at a park on the banks of the River Seine.
[src:abstract-expressionism/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] It is held in the collection of the Art Institute of Chicago.
[src:abstract-expressionism/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] Georges Seurat painted *A Sunday Afternoon* between May 1884 and March 1885, and from October 1885 to May 1886, focusing meticulously on the landscape of the park and concentrating on issues of colour, light, and form.
[src:abstract-expressionism/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] The painting is approximately 2 by 3 metres (6.6 ft × 9.8 ft) in size.
[src:abstract-expressionism/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] Seurat completed numerous preliminary drawings and oil sketches before completing his masterpiece.
[src:abstract-expressionism/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] One complete painting, the study featured to the right, measures 27 3/4 x 41 in.
[src:abstract-expressionism/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] (70.5 x 104.1 cm) and is on display in the Metropolitan Museum of Art.
[src:abstract-expressionism/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] Inspired by optical effects and perception inherent in the color theories of Michel Eugène Chevreul, Ogden Rood and others, Seurat adapted this scientific research to his painting.
[src:abstract-expressionism/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] Seurat contrasted miniature dots or small brushstrokes of colors that when unified optically in the human eye were perceived as a single shade or hue.
[src:abstract-expressionism/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] He believed that this form of painting, called Divisionism at the time (a term he preferred) but now known as Pointillism, would make the colors more brilliant and powerful than standard brushstrokes.
[src:abstract-expressionism/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] The use of dots of almost uniform size came in the second year of his work on the painting, 1885–86.
[src:abstract-expressionism/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] The Island of la Grande Jatte is located at the very gates of Paris, lying in the Seine between Neuilly and Levallois-Perret, a short distance from where La Défense business district currently stands.
[src:abstract-expressionism/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] Although for many years it was an industrial site, it has become the site of a public garden and a housing development.
[src:abstract-expressionism/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] When Seurat began the painting in 1884, the island was a bucolic retreat far from the urban center.
[src:abstract-expressionism/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] The painting was first exhibited at the eighth (and last) Impressionist exhibition in May 1886, then in August 1886, dominating the second Salon of the Société des Artistes Indépendants, of which Seurat had been a founder in 1884.
[src:abstract-expressionism/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] Seurat was extremely disciplined, always serious, and private to the point of secretiveness—for the most part, steering his own steady course.
[src:abstract-expressionism/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] As a painter, he wanted to make a difference in the history of art.
[src:abstract-expressionism/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] With *La Grande Jatte*, Seurat was immediately acknowledged as the leader of a new and rebellious form of Impressionism called Neo-Impressionism.
[src:abstract-expressionism/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] Seurat's painting was a mirror impression of his own painting, *Bathers at Asnières*, completed shortly before, in 1884.
[src:abstract-expressionism/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] Whereas the bathers in that earlier painting are doused in light, almost every figure on *La Grande Jatte* appears to be cast in the shadow, either under trees or an umbrella, or from another person.
[src:abstract-expressionism/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] For Parisians, Sunday was the day to escape the heat of the city and head for the shade of the trees and the cool breezes that came off the river.
[src:abstract-expressionism/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] And at first glance, the viewer sees many different people relaxing in a park by the river.
[src:abstract-expressionism/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] On the right, a fashionable couple, the woman with the sunshade and the man in his top hat, are on a stroll.
[src:abstract-expressionism/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] On the left, another woman who is also well dressed extends her fishing pole over the water.
[src:abstract-expressionism/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] There is a small man with the black hat and thin cane looking at the river, and a white dog with a brown head, a woman knitting, a man playing a trumpet, two soldiers standing at attention as the musician plays, and a woman hunched under an orange umbrella.
[src:abstract-expressionism/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] Seurat also painted a man with a pipe, a woman under a parasol in a boat filled with rowers, and a couple admiring their infant child.
[src:abstract-expressionism/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] Some of the characters are doing curious things.
[src:abstract-expressionism/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] The lady on the right side has a pet monkey on a leash.
[src:abstract-expressionism/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] A lady on the left near the river bank is fishing.
[src:abstract-expressionism/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] The area was known at the time as being a place to procure prostitutes among the bourgeoisie, a likely allusion of the otherwise odd "fishing" rod.
[src:abstract-expressionism/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] In the painting's center stands a little girl dressed in white (who is not in a shadow), who stares directly at the viewer of the painting.
[src:abstract-expressionism/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] This may be interpreted as someone who is silently questioning the audience.
[src:abstract-expressionism/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] In the 1950s, historian and Marxist philosopher Ernst Bloch drew social and political significance from Seurat's *La Grande Jatte*.
[src:abstract-expressionism/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] The historian's focal point was what he saw as Seurat's mechanical use of the figures and what their static nature said about French society at the time.
[src:abstract-expressionism/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] Afterward, critique of the work often centered on the artist's presumed mathematical and robotic interpretation of the meaning of modernity in Paris.
[src:abstract-expressionism/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] The border of the painting is, unusually, in inverted color, as if the world around them is also slowly inverting from the way of life they have known.
[src:abstract-expressionism/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] Seen in this context, the boy who bathes on the other side of the river bank at Asnières appears to be calling out to them, as if to say, "We are the future.
[src:abstract-expressionism/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] Seurat painted the *La Grande Jatte* in three distinct stages.
[src:abstract-expressionism/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] In the first stage, which was started in 1884, he mixed his paints from several individual pigments and was still using dull earth pigments such as ochre or burnt sienna.
[src:abstract-expressionism/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] In the second stage, during 1885 and 1886, Seurat dispensed with the earth pigments and also limited the number of individual pigments in his paints.
[src:abstract-expressionism/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] This change in his palette was due to his application of the advanced color theories of his time.
[src:abstract-expressionism/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] His intention was to paint small dots or strokes of pure color that would then mix on the retina of the beholder to achieve the desired color impression instead of the usual practice of mixing individual pigments.
[src:abstract-expressionism/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] Seurat's palette consisted of the usual pigments of his time such as cobalt blue, emerald green and vermilion.
[src:abstract-expressionism/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] Additionally, he used the then new pigment zinc yellow (zinc chromate), predominantly for yellow highlights in the sunlit grass in the middle of the painting but also in mixtures with orange and blue pigments.
[src:abstract-expressionism/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] In the century and more since the painting's completion, the zinc yellow has darkened to brown—a color degeneration that was already showing in the painting in Seurat's lifetime.
[src:abstract-expressionism/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] The discoloration of the originally bright yellow zinc yellow (zinc chromate) to a brownish color is due to the chemical reaction of the chromate ions to orange-colored dichromate ions.
[src:abstract-expressionism/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] In the third stage during 1888–89 Seurat added the colored borders to his composition.
[src:abstract-expressionism/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] The results of investigation into the discoloration of this painting have been combined with further research into natural aging of paints to digitally rejuvenate the painting.
[src:abstract-expressionism/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] In 1923, Frederic Bartlett was appointed trustee of the Art Institute of Chicago.
[src:abstract-expressionism/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] He and his second wife, Helen Birch Bartlett, loaned their collection of French Post-Impressionist and Modernist art to the museum.
[src:abstract-expressionism/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] Bartlett who had an interest in French and avant-garde artists and influenced her husband's collecting tastes.
[src:abstract-expressionism/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] *Sunday Afternoon on the Island of La Grande Jatte* was purchased on the advice of the Art Institute of Chicago's curatorial staff in 1924.
[src:abstract-expressionism/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] In conceptual artist Don Celender's 1974–75 book *Observation and Scholarship Examination for Art Historians, Museum Directors, Artists, Dealers and Collectors*, it is claimed that the institute paid $24,000 for the work (over $354,000 in 2018 dollars).
[src:abstract-expressionism/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] In 1958, the painting was loaned for the only time, to the Museum of Modern Art in New York.
[src:abstract-expressionism/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] On 15 April 1958, a fire there, which killed one person on the second floor of the museum, forced the emergency evacuation of the painting, which had been on a floor above the fire, to the Whitney Museum, which adjoined MoMA at the time.
[src:abstract-expressionism/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] Once at the institute, the painting was shown in a variety of framing styles and colors over the years.
[src:abstract-expressionism/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] Then in 2022, a new frame was built that attempted to match as closely as possible what conservators felt was Seurat's most likely intent.
[src:abstract-expressionism/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] The painting is the basis for the 1984 Broadway musical *Sunday in the Park with George* by Stephen Sondheim and James Lapine, which tells a fictionalized story of the painting's creation.
[src:abstract-expressionism/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] Subsequently, the painting is sometimes referred to by the misnomer "*Sunday in the Park*".
[src:abstract-expressionism/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] In Topiary Park (formerly Old Deaf School Park) in Columbus, Ohio, sculptor James T.
[src:abstract-expressionism/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] Mason re-created the painting in topiary form; the installation was completed in 1989.
[src:abstract-expressionism/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] The 1986 John Hughes film *Ferris Bueller's Day Off* featured the painting during a scene at the Art Institute of Chicago.
[src:abstract-expressionism/a-sunday-afternoon-on-the-island-of-la-grande-jatte] This work was featured on *100 Great Paintings*.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] After some initial studies with composer Rubin Goldmark, Copland traveled to Paris, where he first studied with Isidor Philipp and Paul Vidal, then with noted pedagogue Nadia Boulanger.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] He studied three years with Boulanger, whose eclectic approach to music inspired his own broad taste.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Determined upon his return to the U.S. to make his way as a full-time composer, Copland gave lecture-recitals, wrote works on commission and did some teaching and writing.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] But he found that composing orchestral music in a modernist style, which he had adopted while studying abroad, was unprofitable, particularly in light of the Great Depression.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] He shifted in the mid-1930s to a more accessible musical style that mirrored the German idea of *Gebrauchsmusik* ("music for use"), music that could serve utilitarian and artistic purposes.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] During the Depression years, he traveled extensively to Europe, Africa, and Mexico, formed an important friendship with Mexican composer Carlos Chávez, and began composing his signature works.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] During the late 1940s, Copland became aware that Stravinsky and other fellow composers had begun to study Arnold Schoenberg's use of twelve-tone (serial) techniques.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] After he had been exposed to the works of French composer Pierre Boulez, he incorporated serial techniques into his *Piano Quartet* (1950), *Piano Fantasy* (1957), *Connotations* for orchestra (1961), and *Inscape* for orchestra (1967).
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Unlike Schoenberg, Copland used his tone rows in much the same fashion as his tonal material—as sources for melodies and harmonies, rather than as complete statements in their own right, except for crucial events from a structural point of view.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] From the 1960s onward, Copland's activities turned more from composing to conducting.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] He became a frequent guest conductor of orchestras in the U.S. and the UK and made a series of recordings of his music, primarily for Columbia Records.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Aaron Copland was born in Brooklyn, New York, on November 14, 1900.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] He was the youngest of five children in a Conservative Jewish immigrant family of Lithuanian origin.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] While emigrating from Russia to the United States, Copland's father, Harris Morris Copland, lived and worked in Scotland for two to three years to pay for his boat fare to the United States.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] It was there that Copland's father may have Anglicized his surname "Kaplan" to "Copland", though Copland himself believed for many years that the change had been caused by an Ellis Island immigration official when his father entered the country.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Copland was unaware until late in his life that the family name had been Kaplan, his parents having never told him.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Throughout his childhood, Copland and his family lived above his parents' Brooklyn shop, H.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Copland's, at 628 Washington Avenue (which Aaron later called "a kind of neighborhood Macy's"), on the corner of Dean Street and Washington Avenue, and most of the children helped out in the store.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] The family members were active in Congregation Baith Israel Anshei Emes, where Aaron celebrated his bar mitzvah, for which he studied under Israel Goldfarb.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Not especially athletic, the sensitive young man became an avid reader and often read Horatio Alger stories on his front steps.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Copland's father had no musical interest.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] His mother, Sarah Mittenthal Copland, sang, played the piano, and arranged music lessons for her children.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Copland had four older siblings: two brothers, Ralph and Leon, and two sisters, Laurine and Josephine.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Of his siblings, his oldest brother Ralph was the most advanced musically; he was proficient on the violin.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Laurine had the strongest connection with Aaron; she gave him his first piano lessons, promoted his musical education, and supported him in his musical career.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] A student at the Metropolitan Opera School and frequent opera-goer, Laurine also brought home libretti for Aaron to study.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Copland attended Boys High School and in the summer went to various camps.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Most of his early exposure to music was at Jewish weddings and ceremonies, and occasional family musicales.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Copland began writing songs at the age of eight and a half.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] His earliest notated music, about seven bars he wrote when age 11, was for an opera scenario he created and called *Zenatello*.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] From 1913 to 1917 he took piano lessons with Leopold Wolfsohn, who taught him the standard classical fare.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Copland's first public music performance was at a Wanamaker's recital.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] By age 15, after attending a concert by Polish composer-pianist Ignacy Jan Paderewski, Copland decided to become a composer.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] At 16, he heard his first symphony, at the Brooklyn Academy of Music.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] After attempts to further his music study from a correspondence course, Copland took formal lessons in harmony, theory, and composition from Rubin Goldmark, a noted teacher and composer of American music (who had given George Gershwin three lessons).
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Goldmark, with whom Copland studied between 1917 and 1921, gave the young Copland a solid foundation, especially in the Germanic tradition.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] As Copland later said: "This was a stroke of luck for me.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] I was spared the floundering that so many musicians have suffered through incompetent teaching." But Copland also said that Goldmark had "little sympathy for the advanced musical idioms of the day" and his "approved" composers ended with Richard Strauss.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Copland's graduation piece from his studies with Goldmark was a three-movement piano sonata in a Romantic style.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] But he had also composed more original and daring pieces that he did not share with his teacher.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] In addition to regularly attending the Metropolitan Opera and the New York Symphony, where he heard the standard classical repertory, Copland continued his musical development through an expanding circle of musical friends.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] After graduating from high school, he played in dance bands.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Continuing his musical education, he received further piano lessons from Victor Wittgenstein, who found him "quiet, shy, well-mannered, and gracious in accepting criticism".
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Copland's fascination with the Russian Revolution and its promise for freeing the lower classes drew a rebuke from his father and uncles.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] In spite of that, in his early adult life, Copland developed friendships with people who had socialist and communist leanings.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Copland's passion for the latest European music, plus glowing letters from his friend Aaron Schaffer, inspired him to go to Paris for further study.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] An article in *Musical America* about a summer school program for American musicians at the Fontainebleau School of Music, offered by the French government, encouraged Copland further.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] His father wanted him to go to college, but his mother's vote in the family conference allowed him to give Paris a try.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] On arriving in France, he studied at Fontainebleau with pianist and pedagog Isidor Philipp and composer Paul Vidal.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] When Copland found Vidal too much like Goldmark, he switched at the suggestion of a fellow student to Nadia Boulanger, then aged 34.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Boulanger had as many as 40 students at once and employed a formal regimen that Copland had to follow.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Copland found her incisive mind much to his liking and her ability to critique a composition impeccable.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Boulanger "could always find the weak spot in a place you suspected was weak...
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] She also could tell you *why* it was weak [italics Copland]." He wrote in a letter to his brother Ralph, "This intellectual Amazon is not only professor at the Conservatoire, is not only familiar with all music from Bach to Stravinsky, but is prepared for anything worse in the way of dissonance.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] A more charming womanly woman never lived." Copland later wrote: "it was wonderful for me to find a teacher with such openness of mind, while at the same time she held firm ideas of right and wrong in musical matters.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Along with his studies with Boulanger, Copland took classes in French language and history at the Sorbonne, attended plays, and frequented Shakespeare and Company, the English-language bookstore that was a gathering place for expatriate American writers.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Among this group in the heady cultural atmosphere of Paris in the 1920s were Paul Bowles, Ernest Hemingway, Sinclair Lewis, Henry Miller, Gertrude Stein, and Ezra Pound, as well as artists like Pablo Picasso, Marc Chagall, and Amedeo Modigliani.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Also influential on the new music were the French intellectuals Marcel Proust, Paul Valéry, Jean-Paul Sartre, and André Gide; Copland said the latter was his favorite and most read.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Travels to Italy, Austria, and Germany rounded out Copland's musical education.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] During his stay in Paris, he began writing musical critiques, the first on Gabriel Fauré, which helped spread his fame and stature in the music community.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Copland returned to America optimistic and enthusiastic about the future, determined to make his way as a full-time composer.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] He rented a studio apartment on New York City's Upper West Side in the Empire Hotel, close to Carnegie Hall and other musical venues and publishers.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] He remained in that area for the next 30 years, later moving to Westchester County, New York.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Copland lived frugally and survived financially with help from two $2,500 Guggenheim Fellowships in 1925 and 1926 (each of the two equivalent to $45,897 in 2025).
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Lecture-recitals, awards, appointments, and small commissions, plus some teaching, writing, and personal loans, kept him afloat in the subsequent years through World War II.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Also important, especially during the Depression, were wealthy patrons who underwrote performances, helped pay for publication of works, and promoted musical events and composers.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Among them was Serge Koussevitzky, the music director of the Boston Symphony Orchestra, who was known as a champion of "new music".
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Koussevitsky proved to be very influential in Copland's life, perhaps the second most important figure in Copland's career after Boulanger.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Beginning with the Symphony for Organ and Orchestra (1924), Koussevitzky performed more of Copland's music than that of any the composer's contemporaries, at a time when other conductors were programming only a few of Copland's works.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Soon after his return to the United States, Copland was exposed to the artistic circle of photographer Alfred Stieglitz.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Evans's photographs inspired portions of Copland's opera *The Tender Land*.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] In his quest to take up the slogan of the Stieglitz group, "Affirm America", Copland found only the music of Carl Ruggles and Charles Ives upon which to draw.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Without what Copland called a "usable past" in American classical composers, he looked to jazz and popular music, something he had started to do while in Europe.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] In the 1920s, Gershwin, Bessie Smith, and Louis Armstrong were in the forefront of American popular music and jazz.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] By the end of the decade, Copland felt his music was going in a more abstract, less jazz-oriented direction.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] But as large swing bands such as those of Benny Goodman and Glenn Miller became popular in the 1930s, Copland took a renewed interest in the genre.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Inspired by the example of Les Six in France, Copland sought out contemporaries such as Roger Sessions, Roy Harris, Virgil Thomson, and Walter Piston, and quickly established himself as a spokesperson for composers of his generation.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] He also helped found the Copland-Sessions Concerts to showcase these composers' chamber works to new audiences.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Copland's relationship with these men, who became known as "commando unit", was one of both support and rivalry, and he played a key role in keeping them together until after World War II.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] With the knowledge he had gained from his studies in Paris, Copland came into demand as a lecturer and writer on contemporary European classical music.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] From 1927 to 1930 and from 1935 to 1938, he taught classes at The New School for Social Research in New York City.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Eventually, his New School lectures appeared in the form of two books—*What to Listen for in Music* (1937, revised 1957) and *Our New Music* (1940, revised 1968 and retitled *The New Music: 1900–1960*).
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] During this period, Copland also wrote regularly for *The New York Times*, *The Musical Quarterly*, and other journals.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] These articles appeared in 1960 as the book *Copland on Music*.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] During his time at The New School, Copland was active as a presenter and curator, using The New School to present a wide range of composers and artists.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Copland's compositions in the early 1920s reflected the modernist attitude that prevailed among intellectuals, that the arts need be accessible to only a cadre of the enlightened, and that the masses would come to appreciate their efforts over time.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] But mounting troubles with the *Symphonic Ode* (1929) and *Short Symphony* (1933) caused Copland to rethink this approach.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] It was financially unprofitable, particularly during the Depression.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Avant-garde music had lost what cultural historian Morris Dickstein calls "its buoyant experimental edge" and the national attitude toward it had changed.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] In many ways, this shift mirrored the German idea of *Gebrauchsmusik* ("music for use"), as composers sought to create music that could serve a utilitarian as well as artistic purpose.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] This approach encompassed two trends: first, music that students could easily learn, and second, music which would have wider appeal, such as incidental music for plays, movies, radio, etc.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] To this end, Copland provided musical advice and inspiration to The Group Theatre, a company that also attracted Stella Adler, Elia Kazan, and Lee Strasberg.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Philosophically an outgrowth of Stieglitz and his ideals, the Group focused on socially relevant plays by American authors.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Through it and later his work in film, Copland met several major American playwrights, including Thornton Wilder, William Inge, Arthur Miller, and Edward Albee, and considered projects with all of them.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Around 1935 Copland began to compose musical pieces for young audiences, in accordance with the first goal of American Gebrauchsmusik.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] These works included piano pieces (*The Young Pioneers*) and an opera (*The Second Hurricane*).
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] During the Depression years, Copland traveled extensively to Europe, Africa, and Mexico.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] He formed an important friendship with Mexican composer Carlos Chávez and returned often to Mexico for working vacations conducting engagements.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] During his initial visit to Mexico, Copland began composing the first of his signature works, *El Salón México*, completed in 1936.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] In it and in *The Second Hurricane* Copland began "experimenting", as he phrased it, with a simpler, more accessible style.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] This and other incidental commissions fulfilled the second goal of American Gebrauchsmusik, creating music of wide appeal.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Concurrent with *The Second Hurricane*, Copland composed (for radio broadcast) "Prairie Journal" on a commission from the Columbia Broadcast System.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] This was one of his first pieces to convey the landscape of the American West.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] This emphasis on the frontier carried over to his ballet *Billy the Kid* (1938), which along with *El Salón México* became his first widespread public success.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Copland's ballet music established him as an authentic composer of American music much as Stravinsky's ballet scores connected the composer with Russian music and came at an opportune time.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] He helped fill a vacuum for American choreographers to fill their dance repertory and tapped into an artistic groundswell, from the motion pictures of Busby Berkeley and Fred Astaire to the ballets of George Balanchine and Martha Graham, to both democratize and Americanize dance as an art form.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] In 1938, Copland helped form the American Composers Alliance to promote and publish American contemporary classical music.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] He was president of the organization from 1939 to 1945.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] In 1939, Copland completed his first two Hollywood film scores, for *Of Mice and Men* and *Our Town*, and composed the radio score "John Henry", based on the folk ballad.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] While these works and others like them that followed were accepted by the listening public at large, detractors accused Copland of pandering to the masses.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Music critic Paul Rosenfeld, for one, warned in 1939 that Copland was "standing in the fork in the high road, the two branches of which lead respectively to popular and artistic success".
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Even some of Copland's friends, such as composer Arthur Berger, were confused about Copland's simpler style.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] The 1940s were arguably Copland's most productive years, and some of his works from this period cemented his fame.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] His ballet scores for *Rodeo* (1942) and *Appalachian Spring* (1944) were huge successes.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] *Lincoln Portrait* and *Fanfare for the Common Man* became patriotic standards.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Composed from 1944 to 1946, it became Copland's best-known symphony.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] The Clarinet Concerto (1948), scored for solo clarinet, strings, harp, and piano, was a commission piece for band-leader and clarinetist Benny Goodman and a complement to Copland's earlier jazz-influenced work, the Piano Concerto (1926).
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] His *Four Piano Blues* is an introspective composition with a jazz influence.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Copland finished the 1940s with two film scores, one for William Wyler's *The Heiress* and one for the film adaptation of John Steinbeck's novel *The Red Pony*.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] In 1949, Copland returned to Europe, where he found French composer Pierre Boulez dominating the group of postwar avant-garde composers there.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] He also met with proponents of twelve-tone technique, based on the works of Arnold Schoenberg, and found himself interested in adapting serial methods to his own musical voice.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] In 1950, Copland received a U.S.-Italy Fulbright Commission scholarship to study in Rome, which he did the following year.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Around this time, he also composed his Piano Quartet, adopting Schoenberg's twelve-tone method, and *Old American Songs* (1950), the first set of which was premiered by Peter Pears and Benjamin Britten, the second by William Warfield.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] During the 1951–52 academic year, Copland gave a series of lectures under the Charles Eliot Norton Professorship at Harvard University.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] These lectures were published as the book *Music and Imagination*.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Because of his leftist views, which had included his support of the Communist Party USA ticket during the 1936 presidential election and his strong support of Progressive Party candidate Henry A.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Wallace in the 1948 presidential election, Copland was investigated by the FBI during the Red scare of the 1950s.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] He was included on an FBI list of 151 artists thought to have Communist associations and found himself blacklisted, with *A Lincoln Portrait* withdrawn from the 1953 inaugural concert for President Dwight Eisenhower.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Called later that year to a private hearing at the United States Capitol in Washington, D.C., Copland was questioned by Joseph McCarthy and Roy Cohn about his lecturing abroad and his affiliations with various organizations and events.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] McCarthy and Cohn ignored Copland's works, which made a virtue of American values.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Outraged by the accusations, many members of the musical community held up Copland's music as a banner of his patriotism.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] The investigations ceased in 1955 and were closed in 1975.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] The McCarthy probes did not seriously affect Copland's career and international artistic reputation, however taxing as they might have been on his time, energy, and emotional state.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Nevertheless, beginning in 1950, Copland—who had been appalled at Stalin's persecution of Dmitri Shostakovich and other artists—began resigning from participation in leftist groups.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Copland, Pollack writes, "stayed particularly concerned about the role of the artist in society".
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] He decried the lack of artistic freedom in the Soviet Union, and in his 1954 Norton lecture he asserted that loss of freedom under Soviet Communism deprived artists of "the immemorial right of the artist to be wrong." He began to vote Democratic, first for Stevenson and then for Kennedy.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Potentially more damaging for Copland was a sea change in artistic tastes, away from the Populist mores that infused his work of the 1930s and 40s.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Beginning in the 1940s, intellectuals assailed Popular Front culture, to which Copland's music was linked, and labeled it, in Dickstein's words, "hopelessly middlebrow, a dumbing down of art into toothless entertainment".
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] They often linked their disdain for Populist art with technology, new media and mass audiences—in other words, the areas of radio, television and motion pictures, for which Copland either had or soon would write music, as well as his popular ballets.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] While these attacks actually began at the end of the 1930s with the writings of Clement Greenberg and Dwight Macdonald for *Partisan Review*, they were based in anti-Stalinist politics and accelerated in the decades following World War II.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] In Japan, he was taken with the work of Tōru Takemitsu and began a correspondence with him that lasted over the next decade.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Copland revised his text "The New Music" with comments on the styles that he encountered.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] He found much of what he heard dull and impersonal.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Electronic music seemed to have "a depressing sameness of sound", while aleatoric music was for those "who enjoy teetering on the edge of chaos".
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] As he summarized, "I've spent most of my life trying to get the right note in the right place.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] In 1952, Copland received a commission from the League of Composers, funded by a grant from Richard Rodgers and Oscar Hammerstein, to write an opera for television.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] While Copland was aware of the potential pitfalls of that genre, which included weak libretti and demanding production values, he had also been thinking about writing an opera since the 1940s.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] The resulting opera, *The Tender Land*, was written in two acts but later expanded to three.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] As Copland feared, when the opera premiered in 1954 critics found the libretto to be weak.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] In spite of its flaws, the opera became one of the few American operas to enter the standard repertory.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] In 1957, 1958, and 1976, Copland was the music director of the Ojai Music Festival, a classical and contemporary music festival in Ojai, California.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] For the occasion of the Metropolitan Museum of Art Centennial, Copland composed *Ceremonial Fanfare for Brass Ensemble* to accompany the exhibition "Masterpieces of Fifty Centuries." Leonard Bernstein, Piston, William Schuman, and Thomson also composed pieces for the museum's Centennial exhibitions.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] From the 1960s onward, Copland turned increasingly to conducting.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] In 1960, RCA Victor released Copland's recordings with the Boston Symphony Orchestra of the orchestral suites from *Appalachian Spring* and *The Tender Land*; these recordings were later reissued on CD, as were most of Copland's Columbia recordings (by Sony).
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] From 1960 until his death, Copland resided at Cortlandt Manor, New York.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Known as Rock Hill, his home was added to the National Register of Historic Places in 2003 and further designated a National Historic Landmark in 2008.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Copland's health deteriorated through the 1980s, and he died of Alzheimer's disease and respiratory failure on December 2, 1990, in North Tarrytown, New York (now Sleepy Hollow).
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Following his death, his ashes were scattered over the Tanglewood Music Center near Lenox, Massachusetts.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Much of his large estate was bequeathed to the creation of the Aaron Copland Fund for Composers, which bestows over $600,000 per year to performing groups.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Copland never enrolled as a member of any political party.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Nevertheless, he inherited a considerable interest in civic and world events from his father.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] His views were generally progressive and he had strong ties with numerous colleagues and friends in the Popular Front, including Clifford Odets.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] He condemned it as "almost worse for art than the real thing".
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Throw the artist "into a mood of suspicion, ill-will, and dread that typifies the cold war attitude and he'll create nothing".
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] While Copland had various encounters with organized religious thought, which influenced some of his early compositions, he remained agnostic.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] He was close with Zionism during the Popular Front movement, when it was endorsed by the left.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Pollack states that Copland was gay and that the composer came to an early acceptance and understanding of his sexuality.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Like many at that time, Copland guarded his privacy, especially in regard to his homosexuality.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] He provided few written details about his private life, and even after the Stonewall riots of 1969, showed no inclination to "come out".
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] However, he was one of the few composers of his stature to live openly and travel with his intimates.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] They tended to be talented, younger men involved in the arts, and the age-gap between them and the composer widened as he grew older.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Most became enduring friends after a few years and, in Pollack's words, "remained a primary source of companionship".
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Among Copland's love affairs were ones with photographer Victor Kraft, artist Alvin Ross, pianist Paul Moor, dancer Erik Johns, composer John Brodbin Kennedy, and painter Prentiss Taylor.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Victor Kraft became a constant in Copland's life, though their romance might have ended by 1944.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Originally a violin prodigy when the composer met him in 1932, Kraft gave up music to pursue a career in photography, in part due to Copland's urging.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Kraft would leave and re-enter Copland's life, often bringing much stress with him as his behavior became increasingly erratic, sometimes confrontational.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Kraft fathered a child to whom Copland later provided financial security, through a bequest from his estate.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Vivian Perlis, who collaborated with Copland on his autobiography, writes: "Copland's method of composing was to write down fragments of musical ideas as they came to him.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] When he needed a piece, he would turn to these ideas (his 'gold nuggets')." If one or more of these nuggets looked promising, he would then write a piano sketch and eventually work on them at the keyboard.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] The piano, Perlis writes, "was so integral to his composing that it permeated his compositional style, not only in the frequent use in the instrument but in more subtle and complex ways".
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] His habit of turning to the keyboard tended to embarrass Copland until he learned that Stravinsky also did so.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Copland would not consider the specific instrumentation for a piece until it was complete and notated.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Nor, according to Pollack, did he generally work in linear fashion, from beginning to end of a composition.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Instead, he tended to compose whole sections in no particular order and surmise their eventual sequence after all those parts were complete, much like assembling a collage.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Copland himself admitted, "I don't compose.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] I assemble materials." Many times, he included material he had written years earlier.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] If the situation dictated, as it did with his film scores, Copland could work quickly.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Otherwise, he tended to write slowly whenever possible.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Even with this deliberation, Copland considered composition, in his words, "the product of the emotions", which included "self-expression" and "self-discovery".
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] While Copland's earliest musical inclinations as a teenager ran toward Chopin, Debussy, Verdi and the Russian composers, Copland's teacher and mentor Nadia Boulanger became his most important influence.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Copland especially admired Boulanger's total grasp of all classical music, and he was encouraged to experiment and develop a "clarity of conception and elegance in proportion".
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Following her model, he studied all periods of classical music and all forms—from madrigals to symphonies.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] This breadth of vision led Copland to compose music for numerous settings—orchestra, opera, solo piano, small ensemble, art song, ballet, theater and film.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Boulanger particularly emphasized "la grande ligne" (the long line), "a sense of forward motion ... the feeling for inevitability, for the creating of an entire piece that could be thought of as a functioning entity".
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] During his studies with Boulanger in Paris, Copland was excited to be so close to the new post-Impressionistic French music of Ravel, Roussel, and Satie, as well as Les Six, a group that included Milhaud, Poulenc, and Honegger.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Webern, Berg, and Bartók also impressed him.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Copland was "insatiable" in seeking out the newest European music, whether in concerts, score reading or heated debate.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] These "moderns" were discarding the old laws of composition and experimenting with new forms, harmonies and rhythms, and including the use of jazz and quarter-tone music.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Milhaud was Copland's inspiration for some of his earlier "jazzy" works.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] He was also exposed to Schoenberg and admired his earlier atonal pieces, thinking Schoenberg's *Pierrot lunaire* above all others.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Copland named Igor Stravinsky as his "hero" and his favorite 20th-century composer.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Copland especially admired Stravinsky's "jagged and uncouth rhythmic effects", "bold use of dissonance", and "hard, dry, crackling sonority".
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Another inspiration for much of Copland's music was jazz.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Beginning in 1923, he employed "jazzy elements" in his classical music, but by the late 1930s, he moved on to Latin and American folk tunes in his more successful pieces.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Although his early focus of jazz gave way to other influences, Copland continued to make use of jazz in more subtle ways in later works.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Copland's work from the late 1940s onward included experimentation with Schoenberg's twelve-tone system, resulting in two major works, the Piano Quartet (1950) and the Piano Fantasy (1957).
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Copland's compositions before leaving for Paris were mainly short works for piano and art songs, inspired by Liszt and Debussy.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] In them, he experimented with ambiguous beginnings and endings, rapid key changes, and the frequent use of tritones.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] His first published work, *The Cat and the Mouse* (1920), was a piece for piano solo based on the Jean de La Fontaine fable "The Old Cat and the Young Mouse".
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] In *Three Moods* (1921), Copland's final movement is entitled "Jazzy", which he noted "is based on two jazz melodies and ought to make the old professors sit up and take notice".
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] The Symphony for Organ and Orchestra established Copland as a serious modern composer.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Murchinson points out the influence of Igor Stravinsky in the work's nervous, driving rhythms and some of its harmonic language.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Copland in hindsight found the work too "European" as he sought a more consciously American idiom to evoke in his future work.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Visits to Europe in 1926 and 1927 brought him into contact with the most recent developments there, including Webern's Five Pieces for Orchestra, which greatly impressed him.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] In August 1927, while staying in Königstein, Copland wrote *Poet's Song*, a setting of a text by E.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Cummings and his first composition using Schoenberg's twelve-tone technique.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] This was followed by the *Symphonic Ode* (1929) and the Piano Variations (1930), both of which rely on the exhaustive development of a single short motif.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] The other major work of Copland's first period is the *Short Symphony* (1933).
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] In it, music critic and musicologist Michael Steinberg writes, the "jazz-influenced dislocations of meter that are so characteristic of Copland's music of the 1920s are more prevalent than ever".
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Compared to the *Symphonic Ode*, the orchestration is much leaner and the composition itself more concentrated.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] In its combination and refinement of modernist and jazz elements, Steinberg calls the *Short Symphony* "a remarkable synthesis of the learned and the vernacular, and thus, in all its brevity [the work last just 15 minutes], a singularly 'complete' representation of its composer".
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] However, Copland moved from this work toward more accessible works and folk sources.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Copland wrote *El Salón México* between 1932 and 1936, which met with a popular acclaim that contrasted the relative obscurity of most of his previous works.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Inspiration for this work came from Copland's vivid recollection of visiting the "Salon Mexico" dancehall where he witnessed a more intimate view of Mexico's nightlife.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Copland derived his melodic material for this piece freely from two collections of Mexican folk tunes, changing pitches and varying rhythms.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] The use of a folk tune with variations set in a symphonic context started a pattern he repeated in many of his most successful works right on through the 1940s.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] It also marked a shift in emphasis from a unified musical structure to the rhetorical effect the music might have on an audience and showed Copland refining a simplified, more accessible musical language.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Copland's brand of nationalism in his ballets differed from that of European composers such as Béla Bartók, who tried to preserve the folk tones they used as close to the original as possible.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Copland enhanced the tunes he used with contemporary rhythms, textures and structures.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] In what could seem contradictory, he used complex harmonies and rhythms to simplify folk melodies and make them more accessible and familiar to his listeners.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Except for the Shaker tune in *Appalachian Spring*, Copland often syncopates traditional melodies, changes their metric patterns and note values.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] In *Billy the Kid*, he derives many of the work's sparse harmonies from the implied harmonic constructions of the cowboy tunes themselves.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Like Stravinsky, Copland mastered the ability to create a coherent, integrated composition from what was essentially a mosaic of divergent folk-based and original elements.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] In that sense, Copland's Populist works such as *Billy the Kid*, *Rodeo*, *Appalachian Spring* are not far removed from Stravinsky's ballet *The Rite of Spring*.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Within that framework, however, Copland preserved the American atmosphere of these ballets through what musicologist Elliott Antokoletz calls "the conservative handling of open diatonic sonorities", which fosters "a pastoral quality" in the music.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] This is especially true in the opening of *Appalachian Spring*, where the harmonizations remain "transparent and bare, suggested by the melodic disposition of the Shaker tune".
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Variations which contrast to this tune in rhythm, key, texture and dynamics, fit within Copland's compositional practice of juxtaposing structural blocks.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] When Hollywood beckoned concert hall composers in the 1930s with promises of better films and higher pay, Copland saw both a challenge for his abilities as a composer as well as an opportunity to expand his reputation and audience for his more serious works.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] In a departure from other film scores of the time, Copland's work largely reflected his own style, instead of the usual borrowing from the late-Romantic period.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] He often avoided the full orchestra, and he rejected the common practice of using a leitmotif to identify characters with their own personal themes.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] He instead matched a theme to the action, while avoiding the underlining of every action with exaggerated emphasis.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Another technique Copland employed was to keep silent during intimate screen moments and only begin the music as a confirming motive toward the end of a scene.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Virgil Thomson wrote that the score for *Of Mice and Men* established "the most distinguished populist musical style yet created in America".
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Many composers who scored for Western movies, particularly between 1940 and 1960, were influenced by Copland's style, though some also followed the late Romantic "Max Steiner" approach, which was considered more conventional and desirable.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Copland's work in the late 1940s and 1950s included use of Schoenberg's twelve-tone system, a development that he had recognized but not fully embraced.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] He had also believed the atonality of serialized music to run counter to his desire to reach a wide audience.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Copland therefore approached dodecaphony with some initial skepticism.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] While in Europe in 1949, he heard a number of serial works but did not admire much of it because "so often it seemed that individuality was sacrificed to the method".
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] The music of French composer Pierre Boulez showed Copland that the technique could be separated from the "old Wagnerian" aesthetic with which he had associated it previously.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Subsequent exposure to the late music of Austrian composer Anton Webern and twelve-tone pieces by Swiss composer Frank Martin and Italian composer Luigi Dallapiccola strengthened this opinion.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Copland came to the conclusion that composing along serial lines was "nothing more than an angle of vision.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Like fugal treatment, it is a stimulus that enlivens musical thinking, especially when applied to a series of tones that lend themselves to that treatment." He began his first serial work, the "Piano Fantasy", in 1951 to fulfill a commission from the young virtuoso pianist William Kapell.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] The piece became one of his most challenging works, over which he labored until 1957.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] During the work's development, in 1953, Kapell died in an aircraft crash.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Critics lauded the "Fantasy" when it was finally premiered, calling the piece "an outstanding addition to his own oeuvre and to contemporary piano literature" and "a tremendous achievement".
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Serialism allowed Copland a synthesis of serial and non-serial practices.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Before he did this, according to musicologist Joseph Straus, the philosophical and compositional difference between non-tonal composers such as Schoenberg and tonal composers like Stravinsky had been considered too wide a gulf to bridge.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Copland wrote that, to him, serialism pointed in two opposite directions, one "toward the extreme of total organization with electronic applications" and the other "a gradual absorption into what had become a very *freely interpreted tonalism* [italics Copland]".
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] The path he said he chose was the latter one, which he said, when he described his *Piano Fantasy*, allowed him to incorporate "elements able to be associated with the twelve-tone method and also with music tonally conceived".
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] This practice differed markedly from Schoenberg, who used his tone rows as complete statements around which to structure his compositions.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Copland used his rows not very differently from how he fashioned the material in his tonal pieces.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] He saw his rows as sources for melodies and harmonies, not as complete and independent entities, except at points in the musical structure that dictated the complete statement of a row.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p01] Even after Copland started using 12-tone techniques, he did not stick to them exclusively but went back and forth between tonal and non-tonal compositions.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p02] Copland did not consider himself a professional writer.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p02] He called his writing "a byproduct of my trade" as "a kind of salesman for contemporary music".
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p02] As such, he wrote prolifically about music, including pieces on music criticism analysis, on musical trends, and on his own compositions.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p02] An avid lecturer and lecturer-performer, Copland eventually collected his presentation notes into three books, *What to Listen for in Music* (1939), *Our New Music* (1941), and *Music and Imagination* (1952).
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p02] In the 1980s, he collaborated with Vivian Perlis on a two-volume autobiography, *Copland: 1900 Through 1942* (1984) and *Copland Since 1943* (1989).
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p02] Along with the composer's first-person narrative, these two books incorporate 11 "interludes" by Perlis and other sections from friends and peers.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p02] Some controversy arose over the second volume's increased reliance over the first on old documents for source material.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p02] Due to the then-advanced stage of Copland's Alzheimer's and the resulting memory loss, however, this fallback to previous material was inevitable.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p02] The use in both books of letters and other unpublished sources, expertly researched and organized, made them what Pollack terms "invaluable".
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p02] During his career, Copland met and helped hundreds of young composers, whom he met and who were drawn to him by his continual interest and acuity into the contemporary musical scene.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p02] Copland's willingness to foster talent extended to critiquing scores in progress that were presented to him by his peers.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p02] Composer William Schuman writes: "As a teacher, Aaron was extraordinary....
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p02] Copland would look at your music and try to understand what *you* were after [italics Schuman].
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p02] He didn't want to turn you into another Aaron Copland....
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p02] When he questioned something, it was in a manner that might make you want to question it yourself.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p02] Everything he said was helpful in making a younger composer realize the potential of a particular work.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p02] Although Copland studied conducting in Paris in 1921, he remained essentially a self-taught conductor with a very personal style.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p02] Encouraged by Igor Stravinsky to master conducting and perhaps emboldened by Carlos Chavez's efforts in Mexico, he began to direct his own works on his international travels in the 1940s.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p02] By the 1950s, he was also conducting the works of other composers, and after a televised appearance where he directed the New York Philharmonic, Copland became in high demand.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p02] He placed a strong emphasis in his programs on 20th-century music and lesser-known composers, and until the 1970s rarely planned concerts to feature his music exclusively.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p02] Performers and audiences generally greeted his conducting appearances as positive opportunities to hear his music as the composer intended.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p02] His efforts on behalf of other composers could be penetrating but also uneven.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p02] Understated on the podium, Copland modeled his style after other composer/conductors such as Stravinsky and Paul Hindemith.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p02] Critics wrote of his precision and clarity before an orchestra.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p02] Observers noted that he had "none of the typical conductorial vanities".
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p02] Copland's unpretentious charm was appreciated by professional musicians but some criticized his "unsteady" beat and "unexciting" interpretations.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p02] Koussevitzky advised him to "stay home and compose".
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p02] Copland at times asked for conducting advice from Bernstein, who occasionally joked that Copland could conduct his works "a little better".
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p02] Bernstein also noted that Copland improved over time, and he considered him a more natural conductor than Stravinsky or Hindemith.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p02] Eventually, Copland recorded nearly all his orchestral works with himself conducting.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p02] Copland wrote a total of about 100 works which covered a diverse range of genres.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p02] Many of these compositions, especially orchestral pieces, have remained part of the standard American repertoire.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p02] The composer himself pointed out, in summarizing the American character of his music, "the optimistic tone", "his love of rather large canvases", "a certain directness in expression of sentiment", and "a certain songfulness".
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p02] While "Copland's musical rhetoric has become iconic" and "has functioned as a mirror of America", conductor Leon Botstein suggests that the composer "helped define the modern consciousness of America's ideals, character and sense of place.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p02] The notion that his music played not a subsidiary but a central role in the shaping of the national consciousness makes Copland uniquely interesting, for the historian as well as the musician." Composer Ned Rorem states, "Aaron stressed simplicity: Remove, remove, remove what isn't needed....
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p02] Aaron brought leanness to America, which set the tone for our musical language throughout [World War II].
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-copland-p02] Copland's music was prominently featured throughout Spike Lee's 1998 film, *He Got Game*.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-siskind] Siskind was born in New York City, growing up on the Lower East Side.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-siskind] Shortly after graduating from City College, he became a public school English teacher.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-siskind] Siskind was a grade school English teacher in the New York Public School System for 25 years, and began photography when he received a camera as a wedding gift and began taking pictures on his honeymoon.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-siskind] After joining the Young People’s Socialist League, he met Sidonie, also known as Sonia, Glatter in 1917.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-siskind] A few years later, in 1929, he married her in the spring.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-siskind] In 1942, Aaron met Ethel Jones, with whom he stayed for several years.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-siskind] Five years later, he met Cathy Spencer and married her in the summer of 1952.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-siskind] He separated from her in 1956, and divorced her a year later.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-siskind] In the summer of 1959, he met Carolyn Brandt and had his third marriage on June 25, 1960.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-siskind] He remained married until his wife's death on January 30, 1976.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-siskind] Along with the photographs, the book features interviews, stories and rhymes collected by members of the Federal Writers’ Project.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-siskind] The Harlem Document was aimed to showcase the reality of urban life in New York.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-siskind] In the 1940s, Siskind lived above the Corner Book Shop, at 102 Fourth Avenue in Manhattan; he also maintained a darkroom at this location.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-siskind] In 1950 Siskind met Harry Callahan when both were teaching at Black Mountain College in the summer, where he also met Robert Rauschenberg who throughout his life always kept a particular Siskind print on his work wall (see MoMA retrospective 2017).
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-siskind] Later, Callahan persuaded Siskind to join him as part of the faculty of the IIT Institute of Design in Chicago (founded by László Moholy-Nagy as the New Bauhaus).
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-siskind] In 1971 he followed Callahan (who had left in 1961) by his invitation to teach at the Rhode Island School of Design, until both retired in the late 1970s.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-siskind] Siskind used subject material from the real world: close-up details of painted walls and graffiti, tar repair on asphalt pavement, rocks, lava flows, dappled shadows on an old horse, Olmec stone heads, ancient statuary and the Arch of Constantine in Rome, and a series of nudes ("Louise").
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-siskind] Siskind worked all over the world, visiting Mexico in 1955 and the 1970s, and Rome in 1963 and 1967.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-siskind] He did the Tar Series in Providence, Vermont, and Route 88 near Westport, Rhode Island, in the 1980s.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-siskind] He continued making photographs until his death from a stroke on February 8, 1991.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-siskind] In 1936, he created a group within the Photo League in New York, which he called the Feature Group.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-siskind] The group’s collective aim was to produce photographic-centred books.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-siskind] The “Harlem Document” became the most notable project produced by them, which explored the socioeconomic situation that the people living in Harlem were experiencing.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-siskind] In the decades that followed, Siskind’s interest in politics shifted to a more poetic and formal style of photography, zoning on the decay and degeneration found in New York City, and this new style is what garnered him worldwide recognition as a photographer.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-siskind] Siskind’s process revolved around hyper-focusing on what he was photographing, and leaving the background blurry or distractions out of frame.
[src:abstract-expressionism/aaron-siskind] From 1941 to 2022, Siskind’s photographs have been featured in 38 exhibitions at MoMA in New York City.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abel-gance] Born in Paris in 1889, Abel Gance was the illegitimate son of a prosperous doctor, Abel Flamant, and a working-class mother, Françoise Péréthon (or Perthon).
[src:abstract-expressionism/abel-gance] Initially taking his mother's name, he was brought up until the age of eight by his maternal grandparents in the coal-mining town of Commentry in central France.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abel-gance] He then returned to Paris to rejoin his mother, who had by then married Adolphe Gance, a chauffeur and mechanic, whose name Abel then adopted.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abel-gance] Although he later fabricated the history of a brilliant school career and middle-class background, Gance left school at the age of 14, and the love of literature and art which sustained him throughout his life was in part the result of self-education.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abel-gance] He started working as a clerk in a solicitor's office, but after a couple of years he turned to acting in the theatre.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abel-gance] When he was 18, he was given a season's contract at the Royal Park Theatre in Brussels, where he developed friendships with the actor Victor Francen and the writer Blaise Cendrars.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abel-gance] While in Brussels, Gance wrote his first film scenarios, which he sold to Léonce Perret.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abel-gance] Back in Paris in 1909, he acted in his first film, Perret's *Molière*.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abel-gance] At that stage, he regarded the cinema as "infantile and stupid" and was only drawn into film jobs by his poverty, but he nevertheless continued to write scenarios, and often sold them to Gaumont.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abel-gance] During this period he was diagnosed with tuberculosis, often fatal at that time, but after a period of retreat in Vittel he recovered.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abel-gance] With some friends, he established a production company, Le Film Français, and began directing his own films in 1911 with *La Digue (ou Pour sauver la Hollande)*, a historical film which featured the first screen appearance of Pierre Renoir.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abel-gance] Gance tried to maintain a connection with the theatre and he finished writing a monumental tragedy entitled *Victoire de Samothrace*, in which he hoped that Sarah Bernhardt would star.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abel-gance] Its five-hour length, and Gance's refusal to cut it, proved to be a stumbling block.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abel-gance] With the outbreak of World War I, Gance was rejected by the army on medical grounds, and in 1915 he started writing and directing for a new film company, Le Film d'art.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abel-gance] He soon caused controversy with *La Folie du docteur Tube*, a comic fantasy in which he and his cameraman Léonce-Henri Burel created some arresting visual effects with distorting mirrors.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abel-gance] The producers were outraged and refused to show the film.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abel-gance] Gance nevertheless continued working for Film d'Art until 1918, making over a dozen commercially successful films.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abel-gance] His experiments included tracking shots, extreme close-ups, low-angle shots, and split-screen images.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abel-gance] His subjects moved steadily away from simple action films towards psychological melodramas, such as *Mater dolorosa* (1917) starring Emmy Lynn as a neglected wife who has an affair with her husband's brother.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abel-gance] The film was a great commercial success, and it was followed by *La Dixième Symphonie*, another marital drama featuring Emmy Lynn.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abel-gance] Here Gance's mastery of lighting, composition and editing was accompanied by a range of literary and artistic references which some critics found pretentious and alienating.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abel-gance] In 1917, Gance was finally drafted into the army, in its Service Cinématographique, an episode which proved futile and short-lived, but it deepened his preoccupation with the impact of the war and the depression which was caused by the deaths of many of his friends.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abel-gance] When he parted company with Film d'Art over a shortage of funds, Charles Pathé stepped in to underwrite his next film, *J'accuse* (1919), in which Gance confronted the waste and suffering which the war had brought.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abel-gance] He re-enlisted in the Service Cinématographique in order to be able to film some scenes on a real battlefield at the front.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abel-gance] The film made a powerful impact and went on to have international distribution.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abel-gance] Nevertheless, Gance brought an unprecedented level of energy and imagination to the technical realisation of his story, set firstly against the dark and grimy background of locomotives and railway yards, and then among the snow-covered landscapes of the Alps.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abel-gance] He employed elaborate editing techniques and innovative use of rapid cutting which made the film highly influential among other contemporary directors.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abel-gance] The finished film was originally in 32 reels and ran for nearly nine hours, but it was subsequently edited down for distribution.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abel-gance] A modern reconstruction from five different versions, available on DVD, is nearly four and a half hours long, and an almost seven hours long restored version was shown at the 2019 Lumière Film Festival.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abel-gance] In 1921, Gance visited America to promote *J'accuse*.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abel-gance] He was also offered a contract with MGM to work in Hollywood, but he turned it down.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abel-gance] After a brief change of pace for *Au Secours!* (1924), a comic film with Max Linder, Gance embarked on his greatest project, a six-part life of *Napoléon*.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abel-gance] Only the first part was completed, tracing Bonaparte's early life, through the Revolution, and up to the invasion of Italy, but even this occupied a vast canvas with meticulously recreated historical scenes and scores of characters.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abel-gance] The original version of the film ran for around 6 hours.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abel-gance] A shortened version received a triumphant première at the Paris Opéra in April 1927 before a distinguished audience that included the future General de Gaulle.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abel-gance] The length was reduced still further for French and European distribution, and it became even shorter when it was shown in America.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abel-gance] This was not the end of the film's career however.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abel-gance] Gance re-used material from it in later films, and the restoration of the silent film at the beginning of the 1980s confirmed it as his best known work.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abel-gance] Gance embraced the arrival of sound with enthusiasm, and his first production was *La Fin du monde* (1931), an expensive science-fiction film (first planned in 1913/14) about the imminent collision of a comet with the Earth.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abel-gance] The film was a critical and commercial disaster, and thereafter the creative independence which Gance had enjoyed in the previous decade was seriously curtailed.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abel-gance] Gance continued to be a busy film-maker throughout the 1930s, but he characterised most of the films made during this period as ones that he did "not in order to live, but in order not to die".
[src:abstract-expressionism/abel-gance] In 1932 he tried to demonstrate his credentials as a reliable and efficient director by filming a remake of *Mater dolorosa* which he completed within 18 days and within budget.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abel-gance] Among the other 'commercial' works that followed were *Lucrezia Borgia* (1935), with Edwige Feuillère, and *Un Grand Amour de Beethoven* (1937), with Harry Baur.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abel-gance] One of the more personal projects that he was able to undertake was a new version of *J'accuse!* (1938), not so much a remake of his 1919 film as a continuation of it, and conceived as a warning against the new war that he saw impending.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abel-gance] His next film *Paradis perdu*, a melodrama about the First World War, proved successful when it was released after the Fall of France in 1940.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abel-gance] Gance then filmed a popular melodrama called *Vénus aveugle*, which he saw as an allegory of the current state of France and a message of hope directed to the ordinary French people in their time of misfortune.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abel-gance] That year, Gance was denounced as a Jew, and was trying to get his name removed from the list of non-aryens forbidden to practice their profession.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abel-gance] At the feat of pursuing his work, Gance complied with the Vichy government and was among those who saw Philippe Pétain as the means of the country's salvation.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abel-gance] In September 1941 *Vénus aveugle* had its first screening in Vichy, preceded by a speech in which Gance paid tribute to Pétain.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abel-gance] After completing one more film, *Le Capitaine Fracasse*, Gance eventually fled to Spain in August 1943, citing growing hostility from the German authorities in France, and he remained there until October 1945.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abel-gance] In the post-World War II era, his difficulties in getting support for his projects increased, and thus he made few films.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abel-gance] The historical melodrama *La Tour de Nesle* (1954) was his first film in colour, and it provoked some revival of interest in his work, with critics such as François Truffaut making the case for Gance as a neglected *auteur* of genius.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abel-gance] Gance returned to Napoleonic spectacle with *Austerlitz* (1960), and made a further historical pageant in *Cyrano et d'Artagnan* (1963), before moving into television for his final works, also on historical subjects.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abel-gance] Throughout his life Gance kept returning to *Napoléon*, often editing his own footage into shorter versions, adding a soundtrack, sometimes filming new material, and as a result the original 1927 film was lost from view for decades.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abel-gance] After various attempts at reconstruction, the dedicated work of the film historian Kevin Brownlow produced a five-hour version of the film, still incomplete but fuller than anyone had seen since the 1920s.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abel-gance] This version was presented at the Telluride Film Festival in August 1979, with the frail 89-year-old director in attendance.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abel-gance] The occasion brought a belated triumph to Gance's career, and subsequent performances and further restoration made his name known to a worldwide audience.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abel-gance] Abel Gance married three times: in 1912 to Mathilde Thizeau; in 1922 to Marguerite Danis (sister of Ida); and in 1933 to Marie-Odette Vérité (Sylvie Grenade), who died in 1978.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abel-gance] Gance died of tuberculosis in Paris in 1981 at the age of 92.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abel-gance] Abel Gance was interred in the Cimetière d'Auteuil in Paris.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abel-gance] Gance wanted himself to be seen as "the Victor Hugo of the screen", and many assessments have recognised the ambition, the ingenuity and the sweeping romanticism of his films.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abel-gance] Some, such as Léon Moussinac in the 1920s, have pointed to the contradictions in his work between creativity and cliché, the "abundance of original treasures and of banal mediocrity and of poor taste".
[src:abstract-expressionism/abel-gance] One thing that has always been acknowledged is Gance's innovations in the techniques of the cinema.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abel-gance] As well as his multiscreen ventures with Polyvision, he explored the use of superimposition of images, extreme close-ups, and fast rhythmic editing, and he made the camera mobile in unorthodox ways – hand-held, mounted on wires or a pendulum, or even strapped to a horse.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abel-gance] He also made early experiments with the addition of sound to film, and with filming in colour and in 3-D.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abel-gance] There were few aspects of film technique that he did not seek to incorporate in his work, and his influence was acknowledged by contemporaries such as Jean Epstein and later by the French New Wave film-makers.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abel-gance] In the assessment of Kevin Brownlow, "...with his silent productions, *J'accuse*, *La Roue*, and *Napoléon*, [Abel Gance] made a fuller use of the medium than anyone before or since".
[src:abstract-expressionism/abel-gance] Another aspect of Gance's work which has drawn comment from critics is the political stance and implication of his life and films, particularly his identification with strong military leaders.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abel-gance] Whereas *J'accuse* in 1919 suggested Gance's pacifist and anti-establishment attitude, the reactions to *Napoléon* in 1927 saw greater ambivalence, and some commentators even judged it to be an apologia for dictatorship.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abel-gance] This strand of criticism of Gance's reactionary politics has continued through later assessments of him; it has also noted his ardent support for Pétain in the early years of World War II, and subsequently for Charles de Gaulle in the 1960s.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abel-gance] Others have regarded these political interpretations as secondary to Gance's mastery of exuberant spectacle, which frequently had a nationalistic focus.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abel-gance] As one obituary concluded, "Abel Gance was perhaps the greatest Romantic of the screen".
[src:abstract-expressionism/abel-gance] Abel Gance was a member of the jury for Miss France 1938.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abel-gance] He was also a member of the jury for the 1953 Cannes Film Festival, with Jean Cocteau as president.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In the United States, abortion is a divisive issue in politics and culture wars.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Prior to the mid-19th century, English common law formed the basis of abortion law in the colonies and the early Republic.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Connecticut was the first state to regulate abortion in 1821; it outlawed abortion after quickening, the moment in pregnancy when the pregnant woman starts to feel the fetus's movement in the uterus, and forbade the use of poisons to induce one post-quickening.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Many states subsequently passed various laws on abortion until the Supreme Court of the United States decisions of *Roe v.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Bolton* decriminalized abortion nationwide in 1973.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The *Roe* decision imposed a federally mandated uniform framework for state legislation on the subject.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] It also established a minimal period during which abortion is legal, with more or fewer restrictions throughout the pregnancy.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] That basic framework, modified in *Planned Parenthood v.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Casey* (1992), remained nominally in place, although the effective availability of abortion varied significantly from state to state, as many counties had no abortion providers.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 2022, *Roe* and *Casey* were overturned in *Dobbs v.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Jackson Women's Health Organization*, ending protection of abortion rights by the United States Constitution and allowing individual states to regulate any aspect of abortion not preempted by federal law.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Since 1976, the Republican Party has generally sought to restrict abortion access based on the stage of pregnancy or to criminalize abortion, whereas the Democratic Party has generally defended access to abortion and has made contraception easier to obtain.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The abortion-rights movement advocates for patient choice and bodily autonomy, while the anti-abortion movement advocate that the fetus has a right to live.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Historically framed as a debate between the pro-choice and pro-life labels, most Americans agree with some positions of each side.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Support for abortion gradually increased in the U.S. beginning in the early 1970s, and stabilized during the 2010s.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The abortion rate has continuously declined from a peak in 1980 of 30 per 1,000 women of childbearing age (15–44) to 11.3 by 2018.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 2018, 78% of abortions were performed at 9 weeks or less gestation, and 92% of abortions were performed at 13 weeks or less gestation.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] By 2023, medication abortions accounted for 63% of all abortions.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Almost 25% of women will have had an abortion by age 45, with 20% of 30 year olds having had one.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 2019, 60% of women who had abortions were already mothers, and 50% already had two or more children.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Increased access to birth control has been statistically linked to reductions in the abortion rate.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The first state to decriminalize abortion prior to *Roe* was Hawaii.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] As of 2025, Alaska, Arizona, California, Colorado, Illinois, Kansas, Maryland, Michigan, Minnesota, Missouri, Montana, New York, Ohio, Vermont, and Wyoming have a right to abortion in their state constitutions, either explicitly or as interpreted by the state supreme court.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Other states, such as Massachusetts and Oregon, protect abortion under state law.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The state constitutions of Alabama, Arkansas, Louisiana, Tennessee, and West Virginia explicitly contain no right to an abortion, while the state constitution of Nebraska prohibits abortion after the first trimester.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In medical parlance, "abortion" refers only to the end of an intrauterine pregnancy before the embryo or fetus can survive outside the uterus.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] This is inclusive of spontaneous abortion (more commonly referred to as miscarriage or early pregnancy loss) and to induced abortion, where a pregnancy is ended through medication or a medical procedure.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The abortion debate most commonly relates to the induced abortion of a pregnancy, which is also how the term "abortion" is used in a legal sense.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Because abortion has been politicized, there has been a proliferation of ill-defined, inconsistently applied terms with no medical or clinical basis.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Concepts like "late-term abortion", or "partial-birth abortion" are not medical terms and do not have clinical significance.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Similarly, terms like "elective abortion" append unnecessary qualifiers that are not rooted in medical or legal distinctions.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The American College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists recommends using the terms "induced abortion" or simply "abortion" instead.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Additionally, some drugs that do not induce medical abortions, such as levonorgestrel, have been referred to as abortifacients by a US Senator.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Abortion in what eventually became the United States was governed by English Common law, which held that abortion after quickening was murder.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] This was repeated by Henry de Bracton, Matthew Hale, and William Blackstone.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The common law on abortions before quickening was varying.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Some historians argue that abortion was a fairly common practice in the history of the United States, and was not always controversial.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] At a time when society was more concerned with the more serious consequence of women becoming pregnant out of wedlock, family affairs were handled out of public view.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Abortion did not become a public controversy until the health risk of unsafe abortions by (female) unlicensed practitioners was brought to the public attention in the 19th century.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] James Mohr wrote that even though pre-quickening abortion was legal in the first three decades of the 19th century, only 1 in 25 to 1 in 30 pregnancies ended in abortion.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] By the 1850s and 1860s, this number had increased to 1 in 5 or 1 in 6.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] John Keown highlighted some challenges in pinning down the common law view, observing that "evidence of quickening would clearly facilitate prosecution".
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In the mid-18th century, Benjamin Franklin included a recipe for an abortifacient in a math textbook.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1728, Franklin condemned publisher Samuel Keimer for publishing an article on abortion.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] According to biographer Walter Isaacson, Franklin did not have a strong view on the issue.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In *The Speech of Polly Baker*, Franklin places the blame for abortion and infanticide on the sexual double standard against women.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1716, New York passed an ordinance prohibiting midwives from providing abortion.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Founding Father and Second President of the United States John Adams praised the Spartan lawgiver Lycurgus for refusing his sister-in-law from having an abortion even though it prevented him from assuming power.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Thomas Jefferson wrote approving of a quote by Montesquieu that "‘there is among savages another custom . . . it is the cruel practice of abortion." Jefferson added that the Natives stopped the practice after becoming "civilized".
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Within the context of a sex scandal, Connecticut became the first state to regulate abortion by statute in 1821.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Many states subsequently passed various abortion laws.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1829, New York made post-quickening abortions a felony and pre-quickening abortions a misdemeanor.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] This was followed by 10 of the 26 states creating similar restrictions within the next few decades, in particular by the 1860s and 1870s.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The first laws related to abortion were made to protect women from real or perceived risks, and those more restrictive penalized only the provider.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Criminalization did not end the practice of abortion; unlicensed doctors and midwives continued to perform them.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Most of the women receiving abortions from unlicensed practitioners were poor.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Women's safety continued to be a concern, especially after the highly publicized death of Mary Rogers.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Wealthier women could pay willing physicians to broadly interpret health exceptions in their favor.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Euphemistic advertisements for abortifacients offered an assortment of herbal remedies.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] A number of other factors likely played a role in the rise of anti-abortion laws.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] As in Europe, abortion techniques advanced starting in the 17th century, and the conservatism of most in the medical profession with regards to sexual matters prevented the wide expansion of abortion techniques.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Physicians, who were the leading advocates of abortion criminalization laws, appear to have been motivated at least in part by advances in medical knowledge.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Science had discovered that fertilization inaugurated a more or less continuous process of development, which produced a new human being.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Quickening was found to be not more or less crucial in the process of gestation than any other step.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Many physicians concluded that if society considered it unjustifiable to terminate pregnancy after the fetus had quickened, and if quickening was a relatively unimportant step in the gestation process, then it was just as wrong to terminate a pregnancy before quickening as after quickening.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The doctors used flawed math to convince the American Medical Association to accept that pre-quickening abortion should also be outlawed, leading to the raft of state laws banning abortion in the latter half of the 19th century.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Doctors were also influenced by practical reasons to advocate anti-abortion laws.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] For one, abortion providers were usually female midwives without formal training or education.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In an age where the leading doctors in the nation were attempting to standardize the medical profession, these unlicensed practitioners were considered a nuisance to public health.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Despite campaigns to end the practice of abortion, abortifacient advertising was highly effective and abortion was commonly practiced, with the help of a midwife or other women, in the mid-19th century, although they were not always safe.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] While the precise abortion rate was not known, James Mohr's 1978 book *Abortion in America* documented multiple recorded estimates by 19th-century physicians, which suggested that between around 15% and 35% of all pregnancies ended in abortion during that period.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] This era also saw a marked shift in the people who were obtaining abortions.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Before the start of the 19th century, most abortions were sought by unmarried women, who had become pregnant out of wedlock and for which there was much less compassion compared to married women who got an abortion; many of them were wealthy and paid well.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Out of 54 abortion cases published in American medical journals between 1839 and 1880, over half were sought by married women, and well over 60% of the married women already had at least one child.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The sense that married women were now frequently obtaining abortions worried many conservative physicians, who were almost exclusively men.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In the Reconstruction era, much of the blame was placed on the burgeoning women's rights movement.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Although the medical profession expressed hostility toward feminism, many feminists of the era were also opposed to abortion.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In *The Revolution*, a newspaper operated by Elizabeth Cady Stanton and Susan B.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Anthony, an 1869 opinion piece was published arguing that instead of merely attempting to pass a law against abortion, the root cause must also be addressed.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The writer stated that simply passing an anti-abortion law would be "only mowing off the top of the noxious weed, while the root remains. ...
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] No matter what the motive, love of ease, or a desire to save from suffering the unborn innocent, the woman is awfully guilty who commits the deed.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] It will burden her conscience in life, it will burden her soul in death; But oh! thrice guilty is he who drove her to the desperation which impelled her to the crime." To many feminists of this era, abortion was regarded as an undesirable necessity forced upon women by thoughtless men.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The free love wing of the feminist movement refused to advocate for abortion and treated the practice as an example of the hideous extremes to which modern marriage was driving women.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Marital rape and the seduction of unmarried women were societal ills, which feminists believed caused the need to abort, as men did not respect women's right to abstinence.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Feminist opposition to abortion was much less prevalent by the 20th century, and it was feminists and physicians who came to question anti-abortion laws and raise public interest in the 1960s.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1873, Anthony Comstock created the New York Society for the Suppression of Vice, an institution dedicated to supervising the morality of the public.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Later that year, Comstock successfully influenced the United States Congress to pass the Comstock Law, which made it illegal to deliver through the U.S. mail any "obscene, lewd, or lascivious" material.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] It also prohibited producing or publishing information pertaining to the procurement of abortion, birth control, and venereal disease, including to medical students.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The production, publication, importation, and distribution of such materials was suppressed under the Comstock Law as being obscene, and similar prohibitions were passed by 24 of the 37 states.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] By 1900, abortion was normally a felony in every state.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Some states included provisions allowing for abortion in limited circumstances, generally to protect the woman's health or to terminate pregnancies arising from rape or incest.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Most Americans did not view abortion as a crime, and abortions continued to occur and became increasingly available.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The American Birth Control League was founded by Margaret Sanger in 1921; it would become Planned Parenthood Federation of America in 1942.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] By the 1930s, licensed physicians performed an estimated 800,000 abortions a year.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1988, 17 year old Becky Bell died from an infection after an unsafe abortion.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] She lived in Indiana where parental consent was required to have a safe and legal abortion.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Tribe wrote in *Abortion: The Clash of Absolutes* that Bell's best friend said that Becky considered an out-of-state abortion to get around Indiana's parental consent requirement.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] It is possible she performed the abortion herself.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] However it was done, Becky died from an infection that was probably caused by the procedure.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Her parents publicly campaigned against parental consent laws after her death.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Rosie Jimenez died from sepsis in 1977 following an abortion procedure at the home of a midwife who was not licensed to perform abortions.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] She did not go to a licensed physician because the Hyde Amendment barring public Medicaid funding for abortions had gone into effect after surviving a statutory challenge in *Beal v.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Doe* and an Equal Protection challenge in *Maher v.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Abu Hayat was convicted by a Manhattan Court in 1993 for performing an illegal third trimester abortion at his clinic in Alphabet City.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The doctor began the dilation and evacuation procedure which was not legal in the third trimester.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The baby was born alive before the procedure could be completed.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] She was missing an arm that had been severed during the D&E.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Hayat argued that he was protected from criminal conviction by *Roe v.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Wade* based on an argument that the baby had not yet been born when he attempted the procedure.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Another patient was forced to leave Hayat's clinic halfway through a procedure after Dr.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Hayat demanded more money that her husband could not afford to pay.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The patient nearly died and was treated at a local hospital for severe infection caused by pieces of dismembered fetus being left in her uterus.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] 17 year old Sophie McCoy died in 1990 from an infected uterine perforation after receiving an abortion at Dr.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Inequality in access to safe and legal abortions persists to this day whereby many women cannot afford to obtain a legal abortion; in such cases, women may turn to illegal abortion.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In the early 1960s, a controversy centered around children's television host Sherri Finkbine that helped bring abortion and abortion law more directly into the American public eye.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Living in the area of Phoenix, Arizona, Finkbine had had four healthy children; during her pregnancy with her fifth child, she discovered the child might have severe deformities when born.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] This was likely because Finkbine had been taking sleeping pills that she was unaware contained thalidomide, a drug that increases the risk of fetal deformities during pregnancy.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Though Finkbine wanted an abortion, the abortion laws of Arizona only allowed abortions if a pregnancy posed a threat to the woman's life.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The situation gained public attention after Finkbine shared the story with a reporter from *The Arizona Republic*, who disclosed her identity in spite of her requests for anonymity.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] On August 18, 1962, Finkbine traveled to Sweden to obtain a legal abortion, where it was confirmed that the fetus had severe deformities.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1964, Gerri Santoro of Connecticut died trying to obtain an illegal abortion, and her photo became the symbol of an abortion-rights movement.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Some women's rights activist groups developed their own skills to provide abortions to women who could not obtain them elsewhere.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] As an example, in Chicago, a group known as "Jane" operated a floating abortion clinic throughout much of the 1960s.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Women seeking the procedure would call a designated number and be given instructions on how to find "Jane".
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Connecticut* struck down one of the remaining contraception Comstock laws in Connecticut and Massachusetts.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] However, *Griswold* only applied to marital relationships, allowing married couples to buy and use contraceptives without government restriction.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Baird*, to extend the precedent of *Griswold* to unmarried persons as well.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1967, Colorado became the first state to decriminalize abortion in cases of rape, incest, or in which pregnancy would lead to permanent physical disability of the woman.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Similar laws were passed in California, Oregon, and North Carolina.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1970, Hawaii became the first state to legalize abortions on the request of the woman, and New York repealed its 1830 law and allowed abortions up to the 24th week of pregnancy.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Similar laws were soon passed in Alaska and Washington.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1970, Washington held a referendum on legalizing early pregnancy abortions, becoming the first state to legalize abortion through a vote of the people.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] A law in Washington, D.C., which allowed abortion to protect the life or health of the woman, was challenged in the Supreme Court in 1971 in *United States v.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The court upheld the law, deeming that "health" meant "psychological and physical well-being", essentially allowing abortion in Washington, D.C.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] By the end of 1972, 13 states had a law similar to that of Colorado, while Mississippi allowed abortion in cases of rape or incest only and Alabama and Massachusetts allowed abortions only in cases where the woman's physical health was endangered.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In order to obtain abortions during this period, women would often travel from a state where abortion was illegal to one where it was legal.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Wade* was that abortion was illegal in 30 states and legal under certain circumstances in 20 states.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Wade*, 30 states prohibited abortion without exception, 16 states banned abortion except in certain special circumstances (e.g. rape, incest, and health threat to mother), 3 states allowed residents to obtain abortions, and New York allowed abortions generally.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Early that year, on January 22, 1973, the U.S.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Wade* invalidated all of these laws, and set guidelines for the availability of abortion.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The decision returned abortion to its liberalized pre-1820 status.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] *Roe* established that the right of privacy of a woman to obtain an abortion "must be considered against important state interests in regulation".
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Wade*, the Court ruled that a Texas statute forbidding abortion except when necessary to save the life of the mother was unconstitutional.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The Court arrived at its decision by concluding that the issue of abortion and abortion rights falls under the right of privacy in the United States (e.g. federal constitutionally-protected right), in the sense of the right of a person not to be encroached by the state.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In its opinion, it listed several landmark cases where the court had previously found a right to privacy implied by the Constitution.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The Court did not recognize a right to abortion in all cases, saying: "State regulation protective of fetal life after viability thus has both logical and biological justifications.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The Court held that a right to privacy existed and included the right to have an abortion.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The court found that a mother had a right to abortion until viability, a point to be determined by the abortion doctor.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] After viability a woman can obtain an abortion for health reasons, which the Court defined broadly to include psychological well-being.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] A central issue in the *Roe* case and in the wider abortion debate in general is whether human life or personhood begins at conception, birth, or at some point in between.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The Court declined to make an attempt at resolving this issue, writing: "We need not resolve the difficult question of when life begins.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Rather than asserting that human life begins at any specific point, the Court declared that the state has a "compelling interest" in protecting "potential life" at the point of viability.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Wade*, state governments may not prohibit late terminations of pregnancy when "necessary to preserve the life or health of the mother", even if it would cause the demise of a viable fetus.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] This rule was clarified by the 1973 judicial decision *Doe v.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Bolton*, which specifies "that the medical judgment may be exercised in the light of all factors—physical, emotional, psychological, familial, and the woman's age—relevant to the well-being of the patient".
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] It is by this provision for the mother's mental health that women in the U.S. legally choose abortion after viability when screenings reveal abnormalities that do not cause a baby to die shortly after birth.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In the late 1960s, a number of organizations were formed to mobilize opinion both against and for the legalization of abortion.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1966, the National Conference of Catholic Bishops assigned Monsignor James T.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] McHugh to document efforts to reform abortion laws, and anti-abortion groups began forming in various states in 1967.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1968, McHugh led an advisory group which became the National Right to Life Committee.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The forerunner of the NARAL Pro-Choice America was formed in 1969 to oppose restrictions on abortion and expand access to abortion.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Wade*, in late 1973, NARAL became the National Abortion Rights Action League.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In the 1992 case of *Planned Parenthood v.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Casey*, the Court abandoned *Roe's* strict trimester framework but maintained its central holding that women have a right to choose to have an abortion before viability.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] *Roe* had held that statutes regulating abortion must be subject to "strict scrutiny"—the traditional Supreme Court test for impositions upon fundamental Constitutional rights.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The Supreme Court continues to make decisions on this subject.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] On April 18, 2007, it issued a ruling in the case of *Gonzales v.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Carhart*, involving a federal law entitled the Partial-Birth Abortion Ban Act of 2003 which President George W.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The law banned intact dilation and extraction, which opponents of abortion rights referred to as "partial-birth abortion", and stipulated that anyone breaking the law would get a prison sentence up to 2.5 years.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The United States Supreme Court upheld the 2003 ban by a narrow majority of 5–4, marking the first time the Court has allowed a ban on any type of abortion since 1973.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The opinion, which came from justice Anthony Kennedy, was joined by Justices Antonin Scalia, Clarence Thomas, and the two recent appointees, Samuel Alito and Chief Justice John Roberts.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Hellerstedt*, the Supreme Court in a 5–3 decision on June 27, 2016, swept away forms of state restrictions on the way abortion clinics can function.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The Court supported this argument and struck down these two provisions "facially" from the law at issue—that is, the very words of the provisions were invalid, no matter how they might be applied in any practical situation.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] According to the Supreme Court, the task of judging whether a law puts an unconstitutional burden on a woman's right to abortion belongs with the courts, and not the legislatures.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The Supreme Court ruled similarly in *June Medical Services, LLC v.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Russo* on June 29, 2020, in a 5–4 decision that a Louisiana state law, modeled after the Texas law at the center of *Whole Woman's Health*, was unconstitutional.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Like Texas' law, the Louisiana law required certain measures for abortion clinics that, if having gone into effect, would have closed five of the six clinics in the state.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The case in Louisiana was put on hold pending the result of *Whole Woman's Health*, and was retried based on the Supreme Court's decision.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] While the District Court ruled the law unconstitutional, the Fifth Circuit found that unlike the Texas law, the burden of the Louisiana law passed the tests outlined in *Whole Woman's Health*, and thus the law was constitutional.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The Supreme Court issued an order to suspend enforcement of the law pending further review, and agreed to hear the case in full in October 2019.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] It was the first abortion-related case to be heard by President Donald Trump's appointees to the Court, Neil Gorsuch and Brett Kavanaugh.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The Supreme Court found the Louisiana law unconstitutional for the same reasons as the Texas one, reversing the Fifth Circuit.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The judgment was supported by Chief Justice John Roberts who had dissented on *Whole Woman's Health* but joined in judgment as to upholding the court's respect for the past judgment in that case.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In December 2021, the FDA legalized telemedical provision of abortion pills with delivery by mail, after finding this to be safe and effective, and having suspended enforcement of previous restrictions during the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] As of June that year, 31 states allowed the practice, fourteen required the prescribing clinician to be physically present, which effectively banned telemedicine, and five explicitly banned telemedical abortion.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The Supreme Court granted *certiorari* to *Dobbs v.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Jackson Women's Health Organization* in May 2021, a case that challenges the impact of *Roe v.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Wade* in blocking enforcement of a 2018 Mississippi law (the Gestational Age Act) that had banned any abortions after the first 15 weeks.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Oral arguments to *Dobbs* were held in December 2021, and a decision was expected by the end of the 2021–22 Supreme Court term.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] On September 1, 2021, Texas passed the Texas Heartbeat Act, one of the most restrictive abortion laws in the nation, banning most procedures after six weeks.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] On May 2, 2022, a leaked draft majority opinion for *Dobbs*, written by Samuel Alito, set to overturn *Roe* was reported by *Politico*.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] On June 24, 2022, the Supreme Court overruled both *Roe* and *Planned Parenthood v.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Casey* in the *Dobbs* case on originalist grounds that a right to abortion cannot be found in the U.S.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] John Roberts, the Chief Justice of the United States, concurred in the decision to uphold the law at question as constitutional, by a 6–3 vote, but did not support overruling both *Roe* and *Casey*.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] This enabled trigger laws, which had been passed in 13 states, to ban abortions in those states.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Voters in Ohio defeated August 2023 Ohio Issue 1, which intended to make changes to the state's constitution more difficult.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] November 2023 Ohio Issue 1 was then approved by a majority of voters, which added the right to an abortion to the Ohio constitution.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Although states nominally allow abortion to prevent the woman's imminent death, five women have died to pregnancy related issues in Texas alone due to doctors refusing to perform abortions because of the state's abortion law despite the *de jure* legal circumstances.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 2026, 2024 Nevada Question 6 needs to be approved again to enshrine abortion in the state's constitution, while legislators in Hawaii, Virginia, and the state of Washington proposed similar amendments to codify abortion rights in 2026.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Gerardo Flores was convicted of two counts of capital murder in 2005 under Texas' fetal homicide law.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] His girlfriend Erica Basoria testified that she had asked him to step on her stomach because her attempts to induce miscarriage on herself had been unsuccessful.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Flores said he initially refused but she would not relent until he agreed.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Flores admitted to police that he "accidentally, probably" hit Basoria in the face during a fight on the night of the miscarriage.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Basoria told police that he was not abusive.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Texas' fetal homicide law did not allow charges against the mother because she had a right to terminate pregnancy, so only Flores was charged.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 2019 a woman in Alabama was indicted after she was shot in the stomach for intentionally causing the death of "unborn baby Jones by initiating a fight knowing she was five months pregnant".
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Medical abortion via mifepristone and misoprostol was approved for abortion in the United States by the FDA in September 2000.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] As of 2007, it was legal and available in all 50 states, Washington, D.C., Guam, and Puerto Rico.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] It is a prescription drug, but was not initially available to the public through pharmacies; its distribution is primarily restricted to specially qualified licensed physicians, sold by Danco Laboratories under the brand name Mifeprex.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] French pharmaceutical company Roussel-Uclaf, (the company that synthesized mifepristone in 1980 and took it through clinical trials for approval in France by 1988) did not seek US approval, so in the United States legal availability was not initially possible.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The United States banned importation of mifepristone for personal use in 1989, a decision supported by Roussel Uclaf.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1994, Roussel Uclaf gave the U.S. drug rights to the Population Council in exchange for immunity from any product liability claims.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The Population Council sponsored clinical trials in the United States.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The drug went on approvable status from 1996.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Production was intended to begin through the Danco Group in 1996, but they withdrew briefly in 1997 due to a corrupt business partner, delaying availability again.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Mifepristone was approved for abortion in the United States by the FDA in September 2000.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 2016, the US Food and Drug Administration (FDA) approved mifepristone, to end a pregnancy through 70 days gestation (70 days or less since the first day of a woman's last menstrual period).
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The approved dosing regimen is 200 mg of mifepristone taken by mouth (swallowed).
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] 24 to 48 hours after taking mifepristone, 800 mcg (micrograms) of misoprostol is taken buccally (in the cheek pouch), at a location appropriate for the patient.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] As of September 2021, in 32 states, the drug could only be provided by a licensed physician, and in 19 states, the prescribing clinician was required to be physically in the room with the patient while they are taking the drug.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In the midst of the COVID-19 pandemic on December 16, 2021, in light of the difficulties in accessing in-person healthcare services, the FDA approved the distribution of mifepristone via mail.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] On 16 December 2021, the FDA voluntarily adopted a new rule permanently relaxing the requirement that the pill be obtained in person, allowing it to be sent through the mail.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] A prescription is still required, so that a doctor can screen for risk factors that would make taking the pill unsafe for the mother.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In January 2023, the FDA further relaxed rules, allowing any retail pharmacy to become certified to fill mifepristone prescriptions.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Department of Justice stated that USPS mailing of pills for medication abortion, even into states where abortion services are restricted, does not violate federal law.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 2023, online access to abortion medication by mail delivered by the U.S.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Postal Service is currently available to citizens of all states.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In light of the *Dobbs* decision, the Alliance Defending Freedom launched a lawsuit in November 2022 in the Northern District of Texas under Judge Matthew J.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Kacsmaryk to seek to overturn the FDA's original approval of mifepristone.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Judge Kacsmaryk ruled for the Alliance on April 7, 2023, reversing the FDA's approval and banning mifepristone across the United States after seven days.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] A district judge in a separate lawsuit, Thomas O.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Rice of the Eastern District of Washington, ruled that the FDA should not reverse access to mifepristone in 16 states.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Kacsmaryk's ruling was partially reversed by a panel on the Fifth Circuit Court of Appeals, leaving mifepristone on the market but reverting efforts made by the FDA to liberalize its use over seven years.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The case was appealed to the Supreme Court, and on June 13, 2024, the court ruled that the Alliance Defending Freedom lacked standing to bring the suit.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In January 2023, GenBioPro filed suit to overturn state laws that prohibit sale of mifepristone, claiming that such laws are invalid because it is a federally approved drug.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The argument that state laws seeking to ban or restrict the use of mifepristone are preempted by the FDA's decision to make the drug available is supported by a number of Supreme Court decisions, including opinions by the traditionally more conservative Justices.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In March 2023, Wyoming became the first US state to ban the pill.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In April 2023, in a lawsuit brought by 17 US states and the District of Columbia, federal district judge Thomas O.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Rice issued a temporary injunction that the FDA should not reduce access to mifepristone in these states and the district.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In May 2024, the state of Louisiana classified mifepristone and misoprostol as controlled substances, with penalties for possession without a prescription.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The move follows concerns over coerced abortion and has drawn criticism from over 240 doctors in the state.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In December 2025, the states of Florida and Texas filed a lawsuit against the FDA challenging its approval of mifepristone in 2000 and approval of a generic in 2025.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] After regulations on abortion early in pregnancy were ruled constitutional by the 2022 decision *Dobbs v.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Jackson Women's Health Organization*, some states enacted restrictions on abortions and abortion pills.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In January 2023, the United States Department of Justice issued an interpretation of the Comstock Act that it was legal for United States Postal Service employees to deliver the pills in any state, because they could not know whether the pills would be used for an abortion or other purposes.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Alliance for Hippocratic Medicine* lawsuit, federal district judge Matthew J.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Kacsmaryk issued a preliminary injunction suspending the 2000 approval of mifepristone, which would take effect a week later.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The Fifth Circuit reversed parts of Kacsmaryk's injunction, but placed a temporary injunction on the 2016 REMS change to mifepristone.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] On appeal to the Supreme Court, the Court stayed both injunctions on 21 April 2023, with only Justices Samuel Alito and Clarence Thomas stating their dissent.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The stay allowed mifepristone to remain legally available while the lower courts consider the merits of the case.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In June 2024, the US Supreme Court unanimously overturned judge Kacsmaryk's Fifth Circuit decision on the grounds that the Alliance for Hippocratic Medicine had no standing to challenge the FDA's regulations of mifepristone.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The Supreme Court ruled that Alliance for Hippocratic Medicine did not demonstrate that they would suffer harm to warrant standing.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The Court did not rule on the substance of mifepristone, abortion, or the FDA's procedures.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Some drugs are approved by the FDA under subsection H, which has two subparts.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The first sets forth ways to rush experimental drugs, such as aggressive HIV and cancer treatments, to market when speedy approval is deemed vital to the health of potential patients.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The second part of subsection H applies to drugs that not only must meet restrictions for use due to safety requirements, but also are required to meet postmarketing surveillance to establish that the safety results shown in clinical trials are seconded by use in a much wider population.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Until December 2021, Mifepristone was approved under the second part of subsection H.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The result is that women could not pick the drug up at a pharmacy, but were required to receive it directly from a doctor.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The approval of mifepristone under subsection H included a black box warning.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] During the COVID pandemic, and coupled with growing restrictions on abortion access in conservative states, the FDA performed trial runs of telemedical abortions, allowing doctors to prescribe mifepristone and other medical abortion drugs without an in-person visit by the patient.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] By December 2021, the FDA advanced approval to for telemedical abortions for all registered providers. which was made final by 2023.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] As of July 2025, 25 states allowed telemedical abortions, the prescription of medical abortion drugs without an in-person visit to a doctor, without restriction, 13 states allowed abortion but had restrictions on telemedical abortions, and 12 states banned abortion.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The FDA's action, coupled with the *Dobbs* decision, led many conservative states to seek new laws to ban citizens in their states from telemedical abortion, or seeking penalties from those that prescribe that medication from other states.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] As a result, eight states where telemedical abortion was legal passed shield laws shield laws to enable physicians to remotely prescribe abortion medication to patients in states where abortion is banned.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In October 2025, Louisiana Attorney General Liz Murrill and the Alliance Defending Freedom filed Louisiana v.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] FDA against the Food and Drug Administration and Department of Health and Human Services challenging the 2023 Risk Evaluation and Mitigation Strategies (REMS) for mifepristone which removed the in-person dispensing requirement.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The Republican Attorneys General of 21 states filed in support of Louisiana's lawsuit.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The lawsuit is one of several brought by Republican Attorneys General seeking to restrict mifepristone.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Joseph paused the case while the second Trump administration conducts a review of the 2023 REMS.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] On May 1, 2026, Republican-appointed Judges Kyle Duncan, Leslie H.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Engelhardt on the Fifth Circuit Court of Appeals unanimously blocked the 2023 REMS, preventing the mailing of mifepristone country-wide.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] However, the Supreme Court temporarily lifted the Fifth Circuit's order via the shadow docket on May 4, and stayed it for an indefinite period on May 14, over dissent from Alito and Thomas.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The ruling will remain in effect through at least the course of the Louisiana-FDA lawsuit, which is expected to continue into the year 2027.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Beyond limitations pertaining to abortion in the context of federal funding, there is little federal legislation protecting or penalizing abortion in the United States.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The Partial-Birth Abortion Ban Act of 2003, Freedom of Access to Clinic Entrances Act of 1994, and Comstock Act of 1873 are some of the few pieces of existing federal law that provide substantive criminal provisions either protecting or penalizing abortion.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The provisions in the Partial Birth Abortion Ban Act and the Freedom of Access to Clinic Entrances Act cover activity affecting interstate or foreign commerce, to which the former was upheld (against constitutional attack under the 5th amendment) by the Supreme Court in *Gonzales v.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The provisions of the Comstock Act primarily cover activity using the mail or postal system, and the Comstock Act was first upheld by Supreme Court in *Ex parte Jackson* (1878).
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The legality of abortion is frequently a major issue in nomination battles for the U.S.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Nominees typically remain silent on the issue during their hearings, as the issue may come before them as judges.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In 2021, the Women's Health Protection Act, which would protect abortion rights by federal statute, was introduced by Judy Chu.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] House of Representatives but was rejected by the U.S.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] After the *Dobbs* decision, Merrick Garland, then-U.S.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Attorney General, asserted that under federal law, states do not have the power to restrict access to FDA-approved abortion pills.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Currently, 13 states have criminal penalties for performing abortions, regardless of gestational age.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The penalties in states that have made abortion illegal vary, as outlined below.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] This chart lists only the penalties authorized specifically by the state laws which explicitly restrict (or ban) abortions.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The chart does not address the risk of being prosecuted for violating any other law because of the abortion.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] States with criminal penalties that are blocked by a court or have yet to take effect are denoted by a gray background.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Prior to 2021, abortion was legal in all U.S. states, and every state had at least one abortion clinic.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Abortion is a controversial political issue, and regular attempts to restrict it occur in most states.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Two such cases, originating in Texas and Louisiana, led to the Supreme Court cases of *Whole Woman's Health v.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Hellerstedt* (2016) and *June Medical Services, LLC v.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Russo* (2020) in which several Texas and Louisiana restrictions were struck down.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The issue of minors and abortion is regulated at the state level, and 37 states require some parental involvement, either in the form of parental consent or in the form of parental notification.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In certain situations, the parental restrictions can be overridden by a court.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Mandatory waiting periods, mandatory ultrasounds and scripted counseling are common abortion regulations.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Abortion laws are generally stricter in conservative Southern states than they are in other parts of the country.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In 2019, New York passed the Reproductive Health Act (RHA), which repealed a pre-*Roe* provision that banned third-trimester abortions except in cases where the continuation of the pregnancy endangered a pregnant woman's life.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Abortion in the Northern Mariana Islands, a United States Commonwealth territory, is illegal.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Alabama House Republicans passed a law on April 30, 2019, that will criminalize most abortion if it goes into effect.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Dubbed the "Human Life Protection Act", it offers only two exceptions: serious health risk to the mother or a lethal fetal anomaly.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Amendments that would have added cases of rape or incest to the list of exceptions were rejected It will also make the procedure a Class A felony.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Twenty-five male Alabama senators voted to pass the law on May 13.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The next day, Alabama governor Kay Ivey signed the bill into law, primarily as a symbolic gesture in hopes of challenging *Roe v.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Since Alabama introduced the first modern anti-abortion legislation in April 2019, five other states have also adopted abortion laws including Mississippi, Kentucky, Ohio, Georgia and most recently Louisiana on May 30, 2019.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Supreme Court upheld an Indiana state law that requires fetuses which were aborted be buried or cremated.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In a December 2019 case, the court declined to review a lower court decision which upheld a Kentucky law requiring doctors to perform ultrasounds and show fetal images to patients before abortions.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] On June 29, 2020, previous Supreme Court rulings banning abortion restrictions appeared to be upheld when the U.S.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Supreme Court struck down the Louisiana anti-abortion law.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Following the ruling, the legality of laws restricting abortion in states such as Ohio was then called into question.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] It was also noted that Supreme Court Chief Justice John Roberts, who agreed that the Louisiana anti-abortion law was unconstitutional, had previously voted to uphold a similar law in Texas which was struck down by the U.S.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In order to avoid traditional constitutional challenges based on *Roe v.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Plaintiffs sought an order from the U.S.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Supreme Court to stop the law from coming into effect, but the Court issued a denial of the order late on September 1, 2021, allowing the law to remain in effect.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] While unsigned, Chief Justice John Roberts and Justice Stephen Breyer wrote dissenting opinions joined by Justices Elena Kagan and Sonia Sotomayor that they would have granted an injunction on the law until a proper judicial review.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Garland further noted that the United States government has "an obligation to ensure that no state can deprive individuals of their constitutional rights." The Complaint avers that Texas enacted the law "in open defiance of the Constitution".
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] District Court in Austin, Texas includes a declaration that the Texas Act is unconstitutional, and an injunction against state actors as well as any and all private individuals who may bring a SB 8 action.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The idea of asking a federal court to impose an injunction upon the entire civilian population of a state is unprecedented and has drawn eyebrows.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In April 2022 Colorado passed into law its Reproductive Health Equity Act, which assures abortion rights for all citizens of the state.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] On May 25, 2022, Oklahoma imposed a ban on almost all abortions after Oklahoma Governor Kevin Stitt signed House Bill 4327.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The bill bans abortion beginning at conception, with exceptions only in cases of "rape, sexual assault, or incest that has been reported to law enforcement", or if "the abortion is necessary to save the life of a pregnant woman in a medical emergency".
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The law also permits private citizens to file lawsuits against (1) abortion providers (2) any individual who "aids and abets" an induced abortion, including paying for an abortion through insurance or otherwise, or (3) any individuals who *intend* to provide or to aid and abet an induced abortion.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] A lawsuit was immediately filed by the ACLU in opposition to the bill.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] At the time of enactment, Oklahoma was the only U.S. state to have passed a bill imposing such restrictions; the law made Oklahoma the first U.S. state to ban induced abortion procedures since prior to the ruling and implementation of *Roe* in 1973.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] on June 24, 2022, after the Supreme Court overturned *Roe*, Texas and Missouri immediately banned abortions with the exception only if the pregnancy was deemed to be particularly life-threatening.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] On January 28, 2023, the Minnesota state Senate passed a bill guaranteeing women's rights to abortion and other reproductive medicine which was signed into law on January 31.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The bill prohibits state and local governments from attempting to restrict access to sterilization or prenatal care, while also requiring contraceptive cost compensation.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In June 2024 abortion in Iowa was made illegal after 6 weeks of gestation, with exceptions for rape, incest, foetal abnormalities, and the mother's life.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In 2023, five women launched a class action lawsuit against the State of Texas after they were reportedly denied abortions at a clinic in the State despite grave risks to their life.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Four of the women traveled out of state in order to obtain an abortion, while the fifth only received the abortion in Texas when she was hospitalized after the fetus suffered a premature rupture of membranes.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The case argues that the Texas law, which allows abortion if there is a health risk to the mother, is too vague and doctors will not perform an abortion for fear of legal repercussions.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Amid the COVID-19 pandemic, anti-abortion government officials in several American states enacted or attempted to enact restrictions on abortion, characterizing it as a non-essential procedure that can be suspended during the medical emergency.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The orders have led to several legal challenges and criticism by human rights groups and several national medical organizations, including the American Medical Association.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Legal challenges on behalf of abortion providers, many of which were represented by the American Civil Liberties Union and Planned Parenthood, successfully stopped most of the orders on a temporary basis.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] One challenge was made against the FDA's rule on the distribution of mifepristone (RU-486), one of the two-part drug regimen to induce abortions.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Since 2000, it is only available through health providers under the FDA's ruling.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Due to the COVID-19 pandemic, access to mifepristone was a concern, and the American College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists along with other groups sued to have the rule relaxed to allow women to be able to access mifepristone at home through mail-order or retail pharmacies.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] While the Fourth Circuit issued a preliminary injunction against the FDA's ruling that would have allowed wider distribution, the Supreme Court ordered in a 6–3 decision in January 2021 to put a stay on the injunction, maintaining the FDA's rule.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Since 2019, the anti-abortion movement in the United States has sought declarations of "sanctuary cit[ies] for the unborn".
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In June 2019, the city council of Waskom, Texas, voted to outlaw abortion in the city, declaring Waskom a "sanctuary city for the unborn" (the first such city to designate itself as such), as state governments elsewhere in the United States were also drafting abortion bans.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] As of July 2019, there is no abortion clinic in the city.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The Waskom ordinance has led other small cities in Texas, and as of April 2021 in Nebraska, to vote in favor of becoming "sanctuary cities for the unborn".
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] On April 6, 2021, Hayes Center, Nebraska, became the first city in Nebraska to outlaw abortion by local ordinance, declaring itself a "sanctuary city for the unborn." The city of Blue Hill, Nebraska, followed suit and enacted a similar ordinance outlawing abortion on April 13, 2021.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In May 2021, Lubbock, Texas, with a population of less than 270,000, voted to ban abortion with the "sanctuary city for the unborn ordinance", becoming the largest city in the U.S. to ban abortion.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Abortion rights movements have also pushed for similar counterpart legislation in other cities.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The abortion debate has also been extended to the question of who pays the medical costs of the procedure, with some states using the mechanism as a way of reducing the number of abortions.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The cost of an abortion varies depending on factors such as location, facility, timing, type of procedure, and whether or not there is insurance or some other type of financial assistance.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In 2022, a medication abortion cost was about $580 at Planned Parenthood, though it could be more, up to around $800, in other facilities.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] During the first trimester an in-clinic abortion cost up to around $800, though often less; the average cost at Planned Parenthood was about $600.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] A second trimester procedure varied depending on the stage of pregnancy.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The average ranged from about $715 earlier in the second trimester to $1,500–2,000 later in the second trimester.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] A variety of resources from support organizations are available to contribute to the costs of the procedure, as well as travel expenses.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] A variety of organizations offer financial support for people seeking abortions, including travel and other expenses.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Access Reproductive Care–Southeast (ARC Southeast), the Brigid Alliance, the Midwest Access Coalition (MAC), and the National Network of Abortion Funds are examples of such groups.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The Hyde Amendment is a federal legislative provision barring the use of federal Medicaid funds to pay for abortions except for rape and incest.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The provision, in various forms, was in response to *Roe v.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Wade*, and has been routinely attached to annual appropriations bills since 1976, and represented the first major legislative success by the pro-life movement.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The law requires that states cover abortions under Medicaid in the event of rape, incest, and life endangerment.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Under this policy, U.S. federal funding to NGOs that provide abortion is not permitted.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The policy was first announced by President Ronald Reagan in 1984.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] It has been rescinded by Democratic presidents and reinstated by Republican presidents.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The policy was rescinded in 2021 by President Joe Biden and reinstated on January 24, 2025, by President Donald Trump.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Qualifying requirements for performing abortions vary from state to state.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Vermont has allowed physician assistants to do some first-trimester abortions since the mid-1970s.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] More recently, several states have changed their requirements for abortion providers, anticipating that the Supreme Court would overturn *Roe v.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Wade*; now that the court has done so, more states are expanding eligibility to provide abortions.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In other states, non-physicians are not permitted to perform abortions.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Because reporting of abortions is not mandatory, statistics are of varying reliability.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Both the Centers For Disease Control (CDC) and the Guttmacher Institute regularly compile these statistics.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] However, in 2024 the Guttmacher Institute raised alarm that the Trump administration has severely gutted CDC efforts to collect these data.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The annual number of legal induced abortions in the U.S. doubled between 1973 and 1979, and peaked in 1990.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] There was a slow but steady decline throughout the 1990s.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Overall, the number of annual abortions decreased by 6% between 2000 and 2009, with temporary spikes in 2002 and 2006.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] By 2011, abortion rate in the nation dropped to its lowest point since the Supreme Court legalized the procedure.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] According to a study performed by Guttmacher Institute, long-acting contraceptive methods had a significant impact in reducing unwanted pregnancies.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] There were fewer than 17 abortions for every 1,000 women of child-bearing age.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] That was a 13%-decrease from 2008's numbers and slightly higher than the rate in 1973, when the Supreme Court's *Roe v.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The study indicated a long-term decline in the abortion rate.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In 2016, the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) reported 623,471 abortions, a 2% decrease from 636,902 in 2015.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] During the first six months of 2023 (following *Dobbs* in 2022), the numbers of abortions in certain U.S. states changed dramatically compared to the same time period in 2020, according to the Guttmacher Institute.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Abortions tripled in New Mexico and Wyoming and more than doubled in South Carolina and Kansas.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] For 13 states that had banned abortion, the Guttmacher Institute had no 2023 data to make the comparison.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] A Guttmacher Institute survey of abortion providers estimated that early medical abortions accounted for 17% of all non-hospital abortions and slightly over one-quarter of abortions before 9 weeks gestation in the United States in 2008.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Medical abortions accounted for 32% of first-trimester abortions at Planned Parenthood clinics in 2008.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] By 2020, medication abortions accounted for more than 50% of all abortions.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In 2023, medication abortions obtained within the formal health care system had risen to 63% of all abortions, with the total percentage (which would include self-managed abortions by individuals in states with total bans) likely higher.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] A majority of abortions are obtained by religiously identified women.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] According to the Guttmacher Institute, "more than 7 in 10 U.S. women obtaining an abortion report a religious affiliation (37% Protestant, 28% Catholic, and 7% other), and 25% attend religious services at least once a month.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Abortion rates tend to be higher among minority women in the United States.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In 2000–2001, the rates among black and Hispanic women were 49 per 1,000 and 33 per 1,000, respectively, vs.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] 13 per 1,000 among non-Hispanic white women.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] This figure includes all women of reproductive age, including women that are not pregnant.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In other words, these abortion rates reflect the rate at which U.S. women of reproductive age have an abortion each year.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In 2004, the rates of abortion by ethnicity in the U.S. were 50 abortions per 1,000 black women, 28 abortions per 1,000 Hispanic women, and 11 abortions per 1,000 white women.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Wade legalized abortion nationwide in 1973.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In 1972, 41% of abortions were performed on women outside their state of residence, while in 1973 it declined to 21%, and then to 11% in 1974.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In the decade from 2011 to 2020, during which many states increased abortion restrictions, the percentage of women nationwide who traveled out of state for an abortion increased steadily, from 6% in 2011 to 9% in 2020.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Out of state travel for an abortion was much more prevalent in the 29 states hostile to abortion rights, with percentages in those states rising from 9% in 2011 to 15% by 2020, while in states supportive of abortion rights, out of state travel for abortions rose from 2% to 3% between 2011 and 2020.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In 2024, around 155,000 people crossed state lines for abortions, doubling the number in 2020.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In several states the percentage of abortions performed within the state specifically for people who traveled from outside of the state exceeds 15%, with Kansas, New Mexico, and Washington DC exceeding 50%.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Illinois performed the most out-of-state abortions in the US at 23% or 34,900 cases.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In contrast, from 2017 to 2020, the *abortion rate by state of residence* for Missourians went up by 18% from 8.4 to 9.9.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Some out of state travel pertains to locations of population centers in states; if large cities are close to state borders it may be common to cross borders for an abortion.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] For example, Delaware, which is generally supportive of abortion rights, saw 44% of residents obtain their abortions in neighboring states.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The source of this information takes findings into account from 27 nations including the United States, and therefore, these findings may not be typical for any one nation.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In 2000, cases of rape or incest accounted for 1% of abortions.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] A 2008 National Survey of Family Growth (NSFG) shows that rates of unintended pregnancy are highest among Blacks, Hispanics, and women with lower socio-economic status.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] According to the Centers for Disease Control, in 2011, most (64.5%) abortions were performed by ≤8 weeks' gestation, and nearly all (91.4%) were performed by ≤13 weeks' gestation.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Few abortions (7.3%) were performed between 14 and 20 weeks' gestation or at ≥21 weeks' gestation (1.4%).
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] From 2002 to 2011, the percentage of all abortions performed at ≤8 weeks' gestation increased 6%.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The risk of death from carrying a child to term in the U.S. is approximately 14 times greater than the risk of death from a legal abortion.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In 2012, the mortality rate from legal abortion was 0.6 abortion-related deaths per 100,000 abortions.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The risk of abortion-related mortality increases with gestational age, but remains lower than that of childbirth through at least 21 weeks' gestation.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] For the period 2013 – 2019, the rate of mortality from legal abortion procedures in the US was 0.43 abortion-related deaths per 100,000 reported legal abortions, lower than the rates for previous 5-year periods.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In 2019, there were four identified deaths related to abortion in the US, out of 625,000 abortions.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] As an element of family planning, birth control was federally subsidized for low income families in 1965 under President Lyndon B.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In 1970, Congress passed Title X to provide family planning services for those in need, and President Richard Nixon signed it into law.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Funding for Title X rose from $6 million in 1971 to $61 million the next year, and slowly increased each year to $317 million in 2010, after which it was reduced by a few percent.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In 2011, the Guttmacher Institute reported that the number of abortions in the U.S. would be nearly two-thirds higher without access to birth control.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In 2015, the Federation of American Scientists reported that federally mandated access to birth control had helped reduce teenage pregnancies in the U.S. by 44 percent, and had prevented more than 188,000 unintended pregnancies.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The level of support for access to abortion has been relatively consistent since 1972.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Large majorities (over 75%) support access to abortion in "traumatic" cases (rape, danger to the mother's health, or strong chance of birth defects) and approximately 40-50% support elective abortion.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Americans have been equally divided on the issue; a May 2018 Gallup poll indicated that 48% of Americans described themselves as "pro-choice" and 48% described themselves as "pro-life".
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] A July 2018 poll indicated that 64% of Americans did not want the Supreme Court to overturn *Roe v.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The same poll found that support for abortion being generally legal was 60% during the first trimester of pregnancy, dropping to 28% in the second trimester, and 13% in the third trimester.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] In January 2013, a majority of Americans believed abortion should be legal in all or most cases, according to a poll by NBC News and *The Wall Street Journal*.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Approximately 70% of respondents in the same poll opposed *Roe v.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] A poll by the Pew Research Center yielded similar results.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Moreover, 48% of Republicans opposed overturning *Roe*, compared to 46% who supported overturning it.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Gallup declared in May 2010 that more Americans identifying as "pro-life" is "the new normal", while also noting that there had been no increase in opposition to abortion.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] It suggested that political polarization may have prompted more Republicans to call themselves "pro-life".
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The terms "pro-choice" and "pro-life" do not always reflect a political view or fall along a binary; in one Public Religion Research Institute poll, seven in ten Americans described themselves as "pro-choice" while almost two-thirds described themselves as "pro-life".
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The same poll found that 56% of Americans were in favor of legal access to abortion in all or some cases.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] 90% approve of abortion when the health of the woman is endangered, 77.4% when there is a strong chance of defects in the baby that could result from the pregnancy, and 79.5% when the pregnancy is the result of rape.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] A 2022 poll by the Pew Research Center, found that 47% polled said that women who had an illegal abortion should face a penalty.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] 14% said they should face jail time, 16% said a fine or community services and 17% were not sure the penalty.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Wade and significantly reduced access to abortion, dissatisfaction with the country's abortion policies rose to 69% (the highest level in 23 years), of which 46% want fewer restrictions on abortion, a significant increase from previous years.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Since then, a consistent majority of the public has identified as pro-choice, with 52% identifying as pro-choice and 44% as pro-life in May 2023.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Pew Research Center polling shows little change in views from 2008 to 2012; modest differences based on gender or age.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The original article's table also shows by party affiliation, religion, and education level.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Support for the legalization of abortion is significantly higher among more educated adults than less educated, and has been consistently so for decades.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] In 2019, 70% of college graduates support abortion being legal in all or most cases, as well as 60% of those with some college education, compared to 54% of those with a high school degree or less.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] A January 2003 CBS News/*The New York Times* poll examined whether Americans thought abortion should be legal or not, and found variations in opinion which depended upon party affiliation and the region of the country.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The margin of error is +/– 4% for questions answered of the entire sample (overall figures) and may be higher for questions asked of subgroups (all other figures).
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] A January 2026 poll by Pew Research found that support for legal abortion in the U.S. varies by race.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Polls indicates general support of legal abortion during the first trimester, although support drops dramatically for abortion during the second and third trimester.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Since the 2011 poll, support for legal abortion during the first trimester has declined.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] According to Gallup's long-time polling on abortion, the majority of Americans are neither strictly "pro-life" or "pro-choice"; it depends upon the circumstances of the pregnancy.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Gallup polling from 1996 to 2021 consistently reveals that when asked the question, "Do you think abortions should be legal under any circumstances, legal only under certain circumstances, or illegal in all circumstances?", Americans repeatedly answer "legal only under certain circumstances".
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] According to the poll, in any given year 48–57% say legal only under certain circumstances, 21–34% say legal under any circumstances, and 13–19% illegal in all circumstances, with 1–7% having no opinion.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] According to the aforementioned poll, Americans differ drastically based upon situation of the pregnancy, suggesting they do not support unconditional abortions.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Congress outlawed intact dilation and extraction when it passed the Partial-Birth Abortion Ban Act.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] A Rasmussen Reports poll four days after the Supreme Court's opinion in *Gonzales v.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Carhart* found that 40% of respondents "knew the ruling allowed states to place some restrictions on specific abortion procedures." Of those who knew of the decision, 56% agreed with the decision and 32% were opposed.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] An ABC poll from 2003 found that 62% of respondents thought "partial-birth abortion" should be illegal; a similar number of respondents wanted an exception "if it would prevent a serious threat to the woman's health".
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Gallup has repeatedly queried the American public on this issue.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] After *Roe*, there was a national political realignment surrounding abortion.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The abortion-rights movement in the United States initially emphasized the national policy benefits of abortion, such as smaller welfare expenses, slower population growth, and fewer illegitimate births.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The abortion-rights movement drew support from the population control movement, feminists, and environmentalists.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Anti-abortion advocates and civil-rights activists accused abortion-rights supporters of intending to control the population of racial minorities and the disabled, citing their ties to racial segregationists and eugenicist legal reformers.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The abortion-rights movement subsequently distanced from the population control movement, and responded by taking up choice-based and rights-oriented rhetoric similar to what was used in the *Roe* decision.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Opponents of abortion experienced a political shift.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The Catholic Church and the Democratic Party supported an expansive welfare state, wanted to reduce rates of abortion through prenatal insurance and federally funded day care, and opposed abortion at the time of *Roe*.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Afterwards, the anti-abortion movement in the United States shifted more to Protestant faiths that saw abortion rights as part of a liberal-heavy agenda to fight against, and became part of the new Christian right.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The Protestant influence helped make opposition to abortion part of the Republican Party's platform by the 1990s.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Republican-led states enacted laws to restrict abortion, including abortions earlier than *Casey*'s general standard of 24 weeks.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Into the 21st century, although members of both major U.S. political parties come down on either side of the issue, the Republican Party is often seen as being anti-abortion, since the official party platform opposes abortion and considers fetuses to have an inherent right to life.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Republicans for Choice represents the minority of that party.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] In 2006, pollsters found that 9% of Republicans favor the availability of abortion in most circumstances.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Of Republican National Convention delegates in 2004, 13% believed that abortion should be generally available, and 38% believed that it should not be permitted.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The same poll showed that 17% of all Republican voters believed that abortion should be generally available to those who want it, while 38% believed that it should not be permitted.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The Democratic Party platform considers abortion to be a woman's right.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Democrats for Life of America represents the minority of that party.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] In 2006, pollsters found that 74% of Democrats favor the availability of abortion in most circumstances.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Of Democratic National Convention delegates in 2004, 75% believed that abortion should be generally available, and 2% believed that abortion should not be permitted.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The same poll showed that 49% of all Democratic voters believed that abortion should be generally available to those who want it, while 13% believed that it should not be permitted.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The position of U.S. third political parties and other U.S. minor political parties is diverse.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The Green Party supports legal abortion as a woman's right.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The Constitution Party is opposed to abortion.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The issue of abortion has become deeply politicized.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] In 2002, 84% of state Democratic platforms supported the right to having an abortion while 88% of state Republican platforms opposed it.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] This divergence also led to Christian right organizations like Christian Voice, Christian Coalition of America, and Moral Majority having an increasingly strong role in the Republican Party.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The policy was revoked by President Bill Clinton and subsequently reinstated by President George W.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] President Barack Obama overruled this policy by Executive Order on January 23, 2009, and it was reinstated on January 23, 2017, by President Donald Trump.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] On January 28, 2021, President Joe Biden signed a Presidential Memorandum that repealed the restoration of Mexico City policy and also called for the United States Department of Health and Human Services to "suspend, rescind or revoke" restrictions made to Title X.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] President Donald Trump reinstated the policy on January 24, 2025.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The risk of death due to legal abortion has fallen considerably since *Roe v.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Wade* (1973) legalized it; this was due to increased physician skills, improved medical technology, and earlier termination of pregnancy.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] From 1940 through 1970, annual deaths of pregnant women during abortion fell from nearly 1,500 to a little over 100.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] According to the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, the number of women who died in 1972 from illegal abortion was thirty-nine.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The Roe effect is a hypothesis suggesting that since supporters of abortion rights cause the erosion of their own political base by having fewer children, the practice of abortion will eventually lead to the restriction or illegalization of abortion.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The legalized abortion and crime effect is another controversial theory that posits legal abortion reduces crime because unwanted children are more likely to become criminals.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Since *Roe*, there have been numerous attempts to reverse the decision.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] In the 2011 election season, Mississippi placed an amendment on the ballot that redefined how the state viewed abortion.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The personhood amendment defined personhood as "every human being from the moment of fertilization, cloning or the functional equivalent thereof"; if passed, it would have been illegal to get an abortion in the state.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] On July 11, 2012, a Mississippi federal judge ordered an extension of his temporary order to allow the state's only abortion clinic to stay open.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The order was to stay in place until U.S.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] District Judge Daniel Porter Jordan III could review newly drafted rules on how the Mississippi Department of Health would administer a new abortion law.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The law in question came into effect on July 1, 2012.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Between 2008 and 2016, the Turnaway Study followed a group of 1,000 women, two of whom died after giving birth, for five years after they sought an abortion, and compared their health and socio-economic consequences of receiving an abortion or being denied one.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The study found that those who were provided with abortion performed better, and those who were denied one suffered negative consequences.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] *Scientific American* described it as landmark.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] A follow-up Turnaway Study was confirmed to determinate the health and economic impact of *Roe* being overturned, which other scholars also analyzed.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Jackson Women's Health Organization* case, which confirmed the May 2022 leaks obtained by *Politico* and overruled *Roe* and *Planned Parenthood v.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The American Historical Association (AHA) and the Organization of American Historians (OAH) were among those who signed an *amici curiae* brief for *Dobbs*, and were cited, among others, by *Reason*, *Syracuse University News*, and *The Washington Post*.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Joined by at least 30 other academic and scholarly institutions, they condemned "the court's misinterpretation about the history of legalized abortion" and said it has "the potential to exacerbate historic injustices and deepen inequalities in our country".
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] In the wake of state abortion bans and restrictions in the United States, Americans have started traveling to Mexico for abortions, and Mexico has expressed a willingness to help.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Providers openly treat American travelers in several states where abortion remains technically illegal, such as Nuevo Leon, which neighbors Texas.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Following the Supreme Court ruling, abortion is being gradually legalized at the state level, and as of 2025 is legal during the first trimester (before the 13th week after implantation) in twenty states and Mexico City.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Although it is uncommon, women sometimes give birth in spite of an attempted abortion.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Reporting of live birth after attempted abortion may not be consistent from state to state, but 38 were recorded in one study in upstate New York in the two-and-a-half years before *Roe v.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] The movement was not limited to painting but included influential collagists and sculptors, such as David Smith, Louise Nevelson, and others.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] Abstract expressionism was notably influenced by the spontaneous and subconscious creation methods of Surrealist artists like André Masson and Max Ernst.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] Artists associated with the movement combined the emotional intensity of German Expressionism with the radical visual vocabularies of European avant-garde schools like Futurism, the Bauhaus, and Synthetic Cubism.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] Abstract expressionism was seen as rebellious and idiosyncratic, encompassing various artistic styles.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] It was the first specifically American movement to achieve international influence and put New York City at the center of the Western art world, a role formerly filled by Paris.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] Contemporary art critics played a significant role in its development.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] Critics like Clement Greenberg and Harold Rosenberg promoted the work of artists associated with abstract expressionism, in particular Jackson Pollock, through their writing and collecting.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] Rosenberg's concept of the canvas as an "arena in which to act" was pivotal in defining the approach of action painters.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] The cultural reign of abstract expressionism in the United States had diminished by the early 1960s, while the subsequent rejection of the abstract expressionist emphasis on individualism led to the development of such movements as Pop art and Minimalism.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] Throughout the second half of the 20th century, the influence of abstract expressionism can be seen in diverse movements in the U.S. and Europe, including Tachisme and Neo-expressionism, among others.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] The term "**abstract expressionism**" is believed to have first been used in Germany in 1919 in the magazine *Der Sturm* in reference to German Expressionism.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] Alfred Barr used this term in 1929 to describe works by Wassily Kandinsky.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] The term was used in the United States in 1946 by Robert Coates in his review of 18 Hans Hofmann paintings.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] An important predecessor is Surrealism, with its emphasis on spontaneous, automatic, or subconscious creation.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] Jackson Pollock's dripping paint onto a canvas laid on the floor is a technique that has its roots in the work of André Masson, Max Ernst, and David Alfaro Siqueiros.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] The newer research tends to put the exile-surrealist Wolfgang Paalen in the position of the artist and theoretician who fostered the theory of the viewer-dependent possibility space through his paintings and his magazine *DYN*.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] Paalen considered ideas of quantum mechanics, as well as idiosyncratic interpretations of the totemic vision and the spatial structure of native-Indian painting from British Columbia and prepared the ground for the new spatial vision of the young American abstracts.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] His long essay *Totem Art* (1943) had considerable influence on such artists as Martha Graham, Isamu Noguchi, Pollock, Mark Rothko and Barnett Newman.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] Around 1944 Barnett Newman tried to explain America's newest art movement and included a list of "the men in the new movement".
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] Paalen is mentioned twice; other artists mentioned are Gottlieb, Rothko, Pollock, Hofmann, Baziotes, Gorky and others.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] Robert Motherwell is mentioned with a question mark.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] Another important early manifestation of what came to be abstract expressionism is the work of American Northwest artist Mark Tobey, especially his "white writing" canvases, which, though generally not large in scale, anticipate the "all-over" look of Pollock's drip paintings.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] The movement's name is derived from the combination of the emotional intensity and self-denial of the German Expressionists with the anti-figurative aesthetic of the European abstract schools such as Futurism, the Bauhaus, and Synthetic Cubism.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] Additionally, it has an image of being rebellious, anarchic, highly idiosyncratic and, some feel, nihilistic.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] In practice, the term is applied to any number of artists working (mostly) in New York who had quite different styles, and even to work that is neither especially abstract nor expressionist.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] Yet all four artists are classified as abstract expressionists.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] Abstract expressionism has many stylistic similarities to the Russian artists of the early 20th century such as Wassily Kandinsky.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] Although it is true that spontaneity or the impression of spontaneity characterized many of the abstract expressionists' works, most of these paintings involved careful planning, especially since their large size demanded it.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] With artists such as Paul Klee, Kandinsky, Emma Kunz, and later on Rothko, Newman, and Agnes Martin, abstract art clearly implied expression of ideas concerning the spiritual, the unconscious, and the mind.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] Why this style gained mainstream acceptance in the 1950s is a matter of debate.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] American social realism had been the mainstream in the 1930s.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] It had been influenced not only by the Great Depression, but also by the Mexican muralists such as David Alfaro Siqueiros and Diego Rivera.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] The political climate after World War II did not long tolerate the social protests of these painters.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] Abstract expressionism arose during the war and began to be showcased during the early forties at galleries in New York such as The Art of This Century Gallery.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] The post-war McCarthy era was a time of artistic censorship in the United States, but if the subject matter were totally abstract then it would be seen as apolitical, and therefore safe.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] Or if the art was political, the message was largely for the insiders.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] While the movement is closely associated with painting, collagist Anne Ryan and certain sculptors in particular were also integral to abstract expressionism.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] David Smith, and his wife Dorothy Dehner, Herbert Ferber, Isamu Noguchi, Ibram Lassaw, Theodore Roszak, Phillip Pavia, Mary Callery, Richard Stankiewicz, Louise Bourgeois, and Louise Nevelson in particular were some of the sculptors considered as being important members of the movement.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] In addition, the artists David Hare, John Chamberlain, James Rosati, Mark di Suvero, and sculptors Richard Lippold, Raoul Hague, George Rickey, Reuben Nakian, and even Tony Smith, Seymour Lipton, Joseph Cornell, and several others were integral parts of the abstract expressionist movement.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] Many of the sculptors listed participated in the Ninth Street Show, a famous exhibition curated by Leo Castelli on East Ninth Street in New York City in 1951.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] Although the abstract expressionist school spread quickly throughout the United States, the epicenters of this style were New York City and the San Francisco Bay area of California.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] In the 1940s there were not only few galleries (The Art of This Century, Pierre Matisse Gallery, Julien Levy Gallery and a few others) but also few critics who were willing to follow the work of the New York Vanguard.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] There were also a few artists with a literary background, among them Robert Motherwell and Barnett Newman, who functioned as critics as well.
