[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] "The big moment came when it was decided to paint 'just to paint'.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] One of the most vocal critics of abstract expressionism at the time was *The New York Times* art critic John Canaday.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] Meyer Schapiro and Leo Steinberg along with Greenberg and Rosenberg were important art historians of the post-war era who voiced support for abstract expressionism.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] During the early-to-mid 1960s younger art critics Michael Fried, Rosalind Krauss, and Robert Hughes added considerable insights into the critical dialectic that continues to grow around abstract expressionism.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] During the period leading up to and during World War II, modernist artists, writers, and poets, as well as important collectors and dealers, fled Europe and the onslaught of the Nazis for safe haven in the United States.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] A few artists, notably Picasso, Matisse, and Pierre Bonnard remained in France and survived.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] The post-war period left the capitals of Europe in upheaval, with an urgency to economically and physically rebuild and to politically regroup.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] In Paris, formerly the center of European culture and capital of the art world, the climate for art was a disaster, and New York replaced Paris as the new center of the art world.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] Post-war Europe saw the continuation of Surrealism, Cubism, Dada, and the works of Matisse.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] Also in Europe, Art brut, and Lyrical Abstraction or Tachisme (the European equivalent to abstract expressionism) took hold of the newest generation.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] Serge Poliakoff, Nicolas de Staël, Georges Mathieu, Vieira da Silva, Jean Dubuffet, Yves Klein, Pierre Soulages and Jean Messagier, among others are considered important figures in post-war European painting.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] In the United States, a new generation of American artists began to emerge and to dominate the world stage, and they were called *abstract expressionists*.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] Graham's influence on American art during the early 1940s was particularly visible in the work of Gorky, de Kooning, Pollock, and Richard Pousette-Dart among others.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] Gorky's contributions to American and world art are difficult to overestimate.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] His work as lyrical abstraction was a "new language.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] He "lit the way for two generations of American artists".
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] The painterly spontaneity of mature works such as *The Liver Is the Cock's Comb*, *The Betrothal II*, and *One Year the Milkweed* immediately prefigured Abstract expressionism, and leaders in the New York School have acknowledged Gorky's considerable influence.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] The early work of Hyman Bloom was also influential.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] American artists also benefited from the presence of Piet Mondrian, Fernand Léger, Max Ernst, and the André Breton group, Pierre Matisse's gallery, and Peggy Guggenheim's gallery The Art of This Century, as well as other factors.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] Hans Hofmann in particular as teacher, mentor, and artist was both important and influential to the development and success of abstract expressionism in the United States.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] Among Hofmann's protégés was Clement Greenberg, who became an enormously influential voice for American painting, and among his students was Lee Krasner, who introduced her teacher, Hofmann, to her husband, Jackson Pollock.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] During the late 1940s, Jackson Pollock's radical approach to painting revolutionized the potential for all Contemporary art that followed him.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] To some extent, Pollock realized that the journey toward making a work of art was as important as the work of art itself.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] Like Picasso's innovative reinventions of painting and sculpture near the turn of the century via Cubism and constructed sculpture, with influences as disparate as Navajo sand paintings, surrealism, Jungian analysis, and Mexican mural art, Pollock redefined what it was to produce art.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] His move away from easel painting and conventionality was a liberating signal to the artists of his era and to all that came after.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] Abstract expressionism in general expanded and developed the definitions and possibilities that artists had available for the creation of new works of art.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] The other abstract expressionists followed Pollock's breakthrough with new breakthroughs of their own.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] In a sense the innovations of Pollock, de Kooning, Franz Kline, Rothko, Philip Guston, Hans Hofmann, Clyfford Still, Barnett Newman, Ad Reinhardt, Richard Pousette-Dart, Robert Motherwell, Peter Voulkos, and others opened the floodgates to the diversity and scope of all the art that followed them.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] The radical Anti-Formalist movements of the 1960s and 1970s including Fluxus, Neo-Dada, Conceptual art, and the feminist art movement can be traced to the innovations of abstract expressionism.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] Abstract expressionism emerged as a major art movement in New York City during the 1950s and thereafter several leading art galleries began to include the abstract expressionists in exhibitions and as regulars in their rosters.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] Action painting was a style widespread from the 1940s until the early 1960s, and is closely associated with abstract expressionism (some critics have used the terms action painting and abstract expressionism interchangeably).
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] A comparison is often drawn between the American action painting and the French tachisme.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] The term was coined by the American critic Harold Rosenberg in 1952 and signaled a major shift in the aesthetic perspective of New York School painters and critics.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] According to Rosenberg the canvas was "an arena in which to act".
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] To Greenberg, it was the physicality of the paintings' clotted and oil-caked surfaces that was the key to understanding them as documents of the artists' existential struggle.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] Rosenberg's critique shifted the emphasis from the object to the struggle itself, with the finished painting being only the physical manifestation, a kind of residue, of the actual work of art, which was in the act or process of the painting's creation.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] This spontaneous activity was the "action" of the painter, through arm and wrist movement, painterly gestures, brushstrokes, thrown paint, splashed, stained, scumbled and dripped.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] The painter would sometimes let the paint drip onto the canvas, while rhythmically dancing, or even standing in the canvas, sometimes letting the paint fall according to the subconscious mind, thus letting the unconscious part of the psyche assert and express itself.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] All this, however, is difficult to explain or interpret because it is a supposed unconscious manifestation of the act of pure creation.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] In practice, the term abstract expressionism is applied to any number of artists working (mostly) in New York who had quite different styles, and even applied to work which is not especially abstract nor expressionist.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] Pollock's energetic action paintings, with their "busy" feel, are different both technically and aesthetically, to De Kooning's violent and grotesque *Women* series.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] *Woman V* is one of a series of six paintings made by de Kooning between 1950 and 1953 that depict a three-quarter-length female figure.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] He began the first of these paintings, *Woman I*, in June 1950, repeatedly changing and painting out the image until January or February 1952, when the painting was abandoned unfinished.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] The art historian Meyer Schapiro saw the painting in de Kooning's studio soon afterwards and encouraged the artist to persist.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] De Kooning's response was to begin three other paintings on the same theme; *Woman II*, *Woman III* and *Woman IV*.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] During the summer of 1952, spent at East Hampton, de Kooning further explored the theme through drawings and pastels.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] He may have finished work on *Woman I* by the end of June, or possibly as late as November 1952, and probably the other three women pictures were concluded at much the same time.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] The *Woman series* are decidedly figurative paintings.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] Another important artist is Franz Kline.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] Robert Motherwell in his *Elegy to the Spanish Republic* series painted powerful black and white paintings using gesture, surface and symbol evoking powerful emotional charges.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] Meanwhile, other action painters, notably de Kooning, Gorky, Norman Bluhm, Joan Mitchell and James Brooks, used imagery via either abstract landscape or as expressionistic visions of the figure to articulate their highly personal and powerful evocations.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] James Brooks' paintings were particularly poetic and highly prescient in relationship to Lyrical Abstraction that became prominent in the late 1960s and the 1970s.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] Both Hans Hofmann and Robert Motherwell can be comfortably described as practitioners of Action painting and Color field painting.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] In the 1940s Richard Pousette-Dart's tightly constructed imagery often depended upon themes of mythology and mysticism; as did the paintings of Gottlieb, and Pollock in that decade as well.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] Color Field painting initially referred to a particular type of abstract expressionism, especially the work of Rothko, Still, Newman, Motherwell, Gottlieb, Ad Reinhardt and several series of paintings by Joan Miró.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] Greenberg perceived Color Field painting as related to but different from Action painting.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] The Color Field painters sought to rid their art of superfluous rhetoric.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] In general, these artists eliminated recognizable imagery, in the case of Rothko and Gottlieb sometimes using symbols and signs as a replacement of imagery.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] Certain artists quoted references to past or present art, but in general color field painting presents abstraction as an end in itself.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] In pursuing this direction of modern art, artists wanted to present each painting as one unified, cohesive, monolithic image.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] However, Color Field painting has proven to be both sensual and deeply expressive albeit in a different way from gestural abstract expressionism.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] Although abstract expressionism spread quickly throughout the United States, the major centers of this style were New York City and California, especially in the New York School, and the San Francisco Bay area.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] Abstract expressionist paintings share certain characteristics, including the use of large canvases, an "all-over" approach, in which the whole canvas is treated with equal importance (as opposed to the center being of more interest than the edges).
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] The canvas as the *arena* became a credo of Action painting, while the *integrity of the picture plane* became a credo of the Color field painters.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] Although Pollock is closely associated with Action Painting because of his style, technique, and his painterly *touch* and his physical application of paint, art critics have likened Pollock to both Action painting and color field painting.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] Another critical view advanced by Greenberg connects Pollock's allover canvasses to the large-scale *Water Lilies* of Claude Monet done during the 1920s.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] Art critics such as Michael Fried, Greenberg and others have observed that the overall feeling in Pollock's most famous works – his *drip* paintings – read as vast fields of built-up linear elements.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] They note that these works often read as vast complexes of similarly-valued paint skeins and all-over fields of color and drawing, and are related to the mural-sized Monets which are similarly constructed of close-valued brushed and scumbled marks that also read as fields of color and drawing.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] Pollock's use of all-over composition lend a philosophical and a physical connection to the way the color field painters like Newman, Rothko and Still construct their unbroken and in Still's case broken surfaces.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] In several paintings that Pollock painted after his classic *drip* painting period of 1947–1950, he used the technique of staining fluid oil paint and house paint into raw canvas.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] During 1951 he produced a series of semi-figurative black stain paintings, and in 1952 he produced stain paintings using color.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] In Gorky's most effective and accomplished paintings between the years 1941–1948, he consistently used intense stained fields of color, often letting the paint run and drip, under and around his familiar lexicon of organic and biomorphic shapes and delicate lines.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] Another abstract expressionist whose works in the 1940s call to mind the stain paintings of the 1960s and the 1970s is James Brooks.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] Brooks regularly used stain as a technique in his paintings from the late 1940s.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] Brooks began diluting his oil paint to have fluid colors with which to pour and drip and stain into the mostly raw canvas that he used.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] These works often combined calligraphy and abstract shapes.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] During the final three decades of his career, Sam Francis' style of large-scale bright abstract expressionism was closely associated with Color field painting.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] His paintings straddled both camps within the abstract expressionist rubric, Action painting and Color Field painting.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] Having seen Pollock's 1951 paintings of thinned black oil paint stained into raw canvas, Frankenthaler began to produce *stain paintings* in varied oil colors on raw canvas in 1952.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] Her most famous painting from that period is *Mountains and Sea*.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] She is one of the originators of the Color Field movement that emerged in the late 1950s.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] Frankenthaler also studied with Hans Hofmann.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] Hofmann's paintings are a symphony of color as seen in *The Gate,* 1959–1960.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] He was renowned not only as an artist but also as a teacher of art, both in his native Germany and later in the US.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] Hofmann, who came to the United States from Germany in the early 1930s, brought with him the legacy of Modernism.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] As a young artist in pre-First World War Paris, Hofmann worked with Robert Delaunay, and he knew firsthand the innovative work of both Picasso and Matisse.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] Matisse's work had an enormous influence on him, and on his understanding of the expressive language of color and the potentiality of abstraction.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] Hofmann was one of the first theorists of color field painting, and his theories were influential to artists and to critics, particularly to Clement Greenberg, as well as to others during the 1930s and 1940s.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] In 1953 Morris Louis and Kenneth Noland were both profoundly influenced by Helen Frankenthaler's stain paintings after visiting her studio in New York City.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] Returning to Washington, DC., they began to produce the major works that created the *color field movement* in the late 1950s.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] In abstract painting during the 1950s and 1960s, several new directions, like the Hard-edge painting exemplified by John McLaughlin, emerged.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] Meanwhile, as a reaction against the subjectivism of abstract expressionism, other forms of Geometric abstraction began to appear in artist studios and in radical avant-garde circles.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] Greenberg became the voice of *Post-painterly abstraction;* by curating an influential exhibition of new painting that toured important art museums throughout the United States in 1964.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] Color field painting, Hard-edge painting and Lyrical Abstraction emerged as radical new directions.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] Notably Robert Motherwell's series *Elegy to the Spanish Republic* addressed some of those political issues.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] Other books on the subject include *Art in the Cold War*, by Christine Lindey, which also describes the art of the Soviet Union at the same time, and *Pollock and After*, edited by Francis Frascina, which reprinted the Kimmelman article.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] Canadian painter Jean-Paul Riopelle (1923–2002), a member of the Montreal-based surrealist-inspired group Les Automatistes, helped introduce a related style of abstract impressionism to the Parisian art world from 1949.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] Michel Tapié's groundbreaking book, *Un Art Autre* (1952), was also enormously influential in this regard.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] Tapié was also a curator and exhibition organizer who promoted the works of Pollock and Hans Hofmann in Europe.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] By the 1960s, the movement's initial effect had been assimilated, yet its methods and proponents remained highly influential in art, affecting profoundly the work of many artists who followed.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] Abstract expressionism preceded Tachisme, Color Field painting, Lyrical Abstraction, Fluxus, Pop Art, Minimalism, Postminimalism, Neo-expressionism, and the other movements of the sixties and seventies and it influenced all those later movements that evolved.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] Robert Rauschenberg and Jasper Johns in the US formed a bridge between abstract expressionism and Pop art.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] Minimalism was exemplified by artists such as Donald Judd, Robert Mangold and Agnes Martin.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] In the years after World War II, a group of New York artists started one of the first true schools of artists in America, bringing about a new era in American artwork: abstract expressionism.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] This led to the American art boom that brought about styles such as Pop Art.
[src:abstract-expressionism/abstract-expressionism] This also helped to make New York City into a cultural and artistic hub.
[src:abstract-expressionism/artnews] The magazine was founded in New York City by James Clarence Hyde in 1902 as ***Hyde's Weekly Art News***, a single–sheet publication issued weekly, covering news about artists, galleries, museums, and the policies impacting them.
[src:abstract-expressionism/artnews] Hyde had previously worked as a culture reporter for *The New York Herald*.
[src:abstract-expressionism/artnews] In its early years, the magazine was primarily a trade publication for the art industry.
[src:abstract-expressionism/artnews] Hyde renamed the magazine ***American Art News*** in November 1904 and expanded it to include multiple pages and illustrations, publishing weekly during the art season between November and May.
[src:abstract-expressionism/artnews] The same year, James Bliss Townsend, a former art critic at the *Herald*, purchased the magazine from Hyde and became editor.
[src:abstract-expressionism/artnews] As editor, Townsend had generally conservative tastes and disliked modern or avant-garde art, but he softened his stance toward the end of his time leading the magazine.
[src:abstract-expressionism/artnews] Townsend died suddenly in 1921 and the magazine was sold to Samuel W.
[src:abstract-expressionism/artnews] Frankel, a former *Herald* staffer who had left the paper to start an art-focused advertising agency, and Peyton Boswell, a critic who previously wrote for the *Herald* and other publications.
[src:abstract-expressionism/artnews] The magazine was renamed ***The Art News*** in 1923.
[src:abstract-expressionism/artnews] The following year, the magazine began publishing *The Art News Annual*, an annual special issue.
[src:abstract-expressionism/artnews] Frankel had a nervous breakdown and developed pneumonia that caused his death in 1935; his widow and son temporarily took charge of the magazine after his death.
[src:abstract-expressionism/artnews] Frankfurter purchased the magazine in 1936, becoming editor of the publication and president of its publisher Art Foundation Press.
[src:abstract-expressionism/artnews] Frankfurter's ownership stake in the company eventually totaled around 80 percent of the shares.
[src:abstract-expressionism/artnews] The magazine was renamed ***ART News*** in 1941, the same year it switched from weekly to a twice monthly schedule.
[src:abstract-expressionism/artnews] Frankfurter introduced a quarterly magazine titled *Portfolio* as a companion to *The Art News Annual*, covering additional art forms beyond visual art.
[src:abstract-expressionism/artnews] Hess joined the magazine in 1946 as an editorial associate before becoming executive editor under Frankfurter in 1949.
[src:abstract-expressionism/artnews] Both Frankfurter and Hess focused the magazine on exhibition reviews and longer, critical essays on art.
[src:abstract-expressionism/artnews] Hess in particular became known for championing abstract expressionism, action painting, and the New York School of artists, including Jackson Pollock, Willem de Kooning, and Franz Kline.
[src:abstract-expressionism/artnews] *ART News* absorbed the publication *Magazine of Art* in 1953, which had prior been published by the American Federation of Arts.
[src:abstract-expressionism/artnews] In 1962, Frankfurter sold Art Foundation Press to The Washington Post Company, which housed *ART News* and *Portfolio* in its magazine division under *Newsweek*.
[src:abstract-expressionism/artnews] Frankfurter remained editor until his death in 1965 and was succeeded in the role by Hess.
[src:abstract-expressionism/artnews] The magazine's name was shortened again in 1969 to *ARTnews*, which remains its current title.
[src:abstract-expressionism/artnews] In the early 1970s, the magazine was struggling financially and had a relatively small circulation around 33,000.
[src:abstract-expressionism/artnews] Milton Esterow, a former art reporter for *The New York Times*, led a group of investors to purchase *ARTnews* in 1972 from *Newsweek* under a new corporate entity, ARTnews Associates, with Esterow becoming the publisher and editor.
[src:abstract-expressionism/artnews] He told the *Times* that he believed the art world was "underreported" and needed more journalistic coverage, though he continued to publish art and exhibition reviews.
[src:abstract-expressionism/artnews] By 1979, the circulation of *ARTnews* had risen to 68,000, moving ahead of its rival *Art in America*.
[src:abstract-expressionism/artnews] Canadian publisher Harlequin Enterprises invested in the company in 1979, becoming a minority owner and allowing the magazine to expand.
[src:abstract-expressionism/artnews] *ARTnews* and *Antiques World* launched a publishing house in 1980 for books by art critics and industry professionals.
[src:abstract-expressionism/artnews] Esterow's daughter Judith Esterow became associate publisher in 1986, having started at the magazine as a receptionist.
[src:abstract-expressionism/artnews] That year, *The New York Times* described the publication as "the elder statesman of American art magazines".
[src:abstract-expressionism/artnews] Milton Esterow introduced the Top 200 Collectors list in 1990, a special annual issue of the magazine that featured profiles of notable art collectors.
[src:abstract-expressionism/artnews] *ARTnews* partnered with the German company Prestel Publishing in 1991 to launch a new publishing house for artist and photographer monographs.
[src:abstract-expressionism/artnews] The downturn in the art market of the early 1990s put financial strain on the business as it relied on advertising income from galleries and other art market businesses.
[src:abstract-expressionism/artnews] The magazine expanded its ads to broader consumer and luxury goods in the mid-90s, leading to increased revenue.
[src:abstract-expressionism/artnews] Robin Cembalest was named editor of *ARTnews* in 1998.
[src:abstract-expressionism/artnews] To commemorate the magazine's 100th anniversary in 2002, the National Portrait Gallery in Washington organized an exhibition of archival photographs from the magazine of artists and art world figures.
[src:abstract-expressionism/artnews] In 2005, the magazine had a print circulation of 85,000.
[src:abstract-expressionism/artnews] Milton Esterow and his daughter sold the publication in April 2014 to Skate Capital, a private asset-management firm owned by Russian financier Sergey Skaterschikov, for a reported $2 million.
[src:abstract-expressionism/artnews] The magazine had a print circulation of 80,000 at the time.
[src:abstract-expressionism/artnews] The company also announced that it was merging with the parent company of *ARTnews* to form ArtNews SA.
[src:abstract-expressionism/artnews] Sarah Douglas, former culture editor of *The New York Observer*, was named the new editor-in-chief of the publication as part of the transition, replacing Cembalest.
[src:abstract-expressionism/artnews] As part of the process, *ARTnews* and *Art in America* formally merged, with the latter's digital portfolio incorporated into the *ARTnews* website, though the two continued to publish separate print editions.
